aphy information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","3550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384630","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) administers and collects information on student support for each of the UK Government Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>In February 2015, the SLC responded to the Freedom of Information (FOI) request: <em>How many prisoners have received student finance in the UK in the past three years, and how much has been paid? </em>The response provided can be found at the following link: <a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/media/886467/foi_response_199-14.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/media/886467/foi_response_199-14.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the tuition fee loans recovered from these prisoners could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-06-29T13:08:54.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384630/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384630/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Prisons: Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much has been (a) given to and (b) recovered from prisoners in tuition fee loans taken out since September 2012.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384631","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-30","<p /> <p>The EU-US FTA is expected to be a mixed agreement to which the UK is individually a party. As such, it would be subject to agreement by each Member State (including the UK), the EU Council (representing governments of the EU countries) and the European Parliament. As part of this process, the UK Parliament would receive the complete draft text of the agreement in order to scrutinise it through debates in both Houses.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-30T16:37:52.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384631/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384631/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Transatlantic Trade and  Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will ensure that there is a vote in the House before the UK signs up to the Transatlantic Trade Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","3570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384632","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Tier 2 Intra Company Transfer route is designed to allow multinational companies to transfer existing employees to temporary posts in their UK branch. Allowing such businesses to transfer staff in this way can encourage international trade and investment and can create UK jobs for resident workers, not just migrant workers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Intra Company Transfers play an import role in bringing overseas IT professionals to the UK. The majority of applications under this route are for IT occupations. For the year ending September 2014, 76% (16,484) of short-term ICT visas and 47% (7,996) of long-term ICT visas issued were for IT jobs.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T15:38:04.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384632/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384632/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Migrant Workers: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the role of Tier 2 Inter Company Transfer Visas in promoting skills in the ICT industries.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384633","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-29","<p>Widening participation in higher education remains a priority for this Government. The Prime Minister has committed to doubling the proportion of people from disadvantaged backgrounds entering higher education by the end of this Parliament from 2009 levels.</p><p> </p><p>We are reviewing all areas of the Department’s expenditure as part of our preparations for the spending review and no decisions have yet been taken on any funding streams beyond 2015-16.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-06-29T13:07:41.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384633/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384633/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his policy is on maintaining the student opportunity allocation in its current form.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384634","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-25","<p>A budget of £3.91 billion was set for the 2015-16 financial year to fund adult Further Education and Skills. This was published in the Skills Funding Letter in February 2015 although the figure will be subject to revision in the budget.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All spending decisions for 2016-17 and beyond will be taken as part of the Spending Review, the timetable for which is yet to be finalised.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T15:41:16.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384634/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384634/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Skills Funding Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the budget is for the Skills Funding Agency for the next five years; if he will conduct a review into the level of funding of the Skills Funding Agency for each of those years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384635","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-25","<p>Adult skills funding is made available to further education providers, not local areas or regions. The funding system is demand led and money follows the learners.<br> <br></p><p> </p><p>Allocations for 2015-16 will be published for all colleges as a matter of course. These will be made available on the Skills Funding Agency website. Historic allocations are also available on the Skills Funding Agency website.</p><p> </p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2005-to-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2005-to-2013</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2014-to-2015</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T15:39:28.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384635/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384635/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Skills Funding Agency: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the Skills Funding Agency budget has been spent in the West Midlands in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384636","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Cabinet Office does not directly employ any staff on tier 2 intercompany Transfers. It has fewer than five staff on secondment to the department through a tier 2 intercompany transfer. The visa and immigration status of contractors is a matter for the contracting organisation.</p><p> </p><p>Cabinet Office does not hold information regarding the immigration status of other Government Departments’ employees.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-06-26T09:29:10.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384636/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384636/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-22","Government Departments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether any staff on Tier 2 Intercompany Transfers are employed, seconded or contracted to (a) his Department and (b) other Government departments.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384637","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3608 ; 3609","2015-06-25T16:23:16.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384637/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384637/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department has had with the Financial Conduct Authority on the assessment of the resilience of financial IT systems as part of critical national infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384638","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3607 ; 3609","2015-06-25T16:23:17.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384638/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384638/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Royal Bank of Scotland: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons the weaknesses that led to problems with IT systems in RBS in June 2015 were not identified as risks in the National Infrastructure Plan, published in 2013; and what discussions he has had with the Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure on those problems.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384639","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3607 ; 3608","2015-06-25T16:23:16.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384639/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384639/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) fiscal and (b) other incentives are in place for financial services companies to update their IT systems as part of improving the resilience of critical national infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384640","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>None.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-06-29T14:19:38.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384640/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384640/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-22","Cabinet Office: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many non-executive directors of his Department who were in post before May 2015 have since left the Department's board; what the names and length of tenure of such directors were; and how many and what non-executive director appointments he has made since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","3551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384641","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>In announcing the sale of the Government’s shareholding in Royal Bank of Scotland, the Chancellor is acting on independent advice from the Governor of the Bank of England and a report from Rothschild investment bank that it is in the public interest for the Government to begin now to sell its stake. The report by Rothschild, and the corresponding advice from the Governor, are both available online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3587","2015-06-25T14:51:44.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384641/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384641/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2015 to Question 900337, from which bodies he has commissioned advice on the sale of Royal Bank of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","3514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384642","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Government has been consistent and clear that its objective in respect of RBS ownership is to return the bank to the private sector in full.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This policy is supported by recent advice from the Governor of the Bank of England that “it is in the public interest for the Government to begin now to return RBS to the private sector”, and that “there could be considerable net costs to taxpayers of further delaying the start of a sale”. The findings of the recently published Rothschild report into the Government’s shareholding in RBS concur with this assessment.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-25T14:44:54.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384642/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384642/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what impact assessment he conducted of (a) the reprivatisation of RBS and (b) any other policy options for the future of RBS before the commissioning of the Rothschild Review into the UK Investment in Royal Bank of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","3499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384643","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-30","<p>The information requested is set out in HM Treasury’s Annual Report and Accounts, copies of which are available in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-30T14:03:43.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384643/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384643/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Treasury: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many non-executive directors of his Department who were in post before May 2015 have since left the Department's board; what the names and length of tenure of such directors were; and how many and what non-executive director appointments he has made since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","3566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384644","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>In announcing the sale of the Government’s shareholding in Royal Bank of Scotland, the Chancellor is acting on independent advice from the Governor of the Bank of England and a report from Rothschild investment bank that it is in the public interest for the Government to begin now to sell its stake. The report by Rothschild, and the corresponding advice from the Governor, are both available online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3514","2015-06-25T14:51:44.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384644/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384644/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2015 to Question 900337, what estimate has been made (a) by the Governor of the Bank of England and (b) from Rothschild of the effect on the public purse of the sale of the Government's stake in the Royal Bank of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","3587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384645","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK introduced legislation in Finance Act 2015 in order to implement the OECD model for Country-by-Country reporting (CbC). This proposal was initiated by the UK under its G8 presidency in 2013 and developed as part of the OECD's Base Erosion and Profit Shifting project.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OECD’s proposed implementation package, which was published on 8 June 2015, requires filing for Multinational Enterprises (MNEs) with fiscal years beginning on or after 1 January 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government will set out further detail on implementation in the UK in line with the international agreement in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-25T15:13:34.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384645/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384645/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to bring forward legislative proposals to ensure that multinational enterprises provide country-by-country tax reports in line with proposals made in the OECD's Country-by-Country Reporting Implementation Package, published in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","3541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384646","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK introduced legislation in Finance Bill 2015 in order to implement the OECD model for Country-by-Country reporting (CbC). This proposal was initiated by the UK under its G8 presidency in 2013 and developed as part of the OECD's Base Erosion and Profit Shifting project.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OECD’s proposed implementation package, which was published on 8 June 2015, requires filing for Multinational Enterprises (MNEs) with fiscal years beginning on or after 1 January 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government will set out further detail on implementation in the UK in line with the international agreement in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-25T14:59:02.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384646/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384646/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many multinational enterprises that paid tax to the Government provided country-by-country tax reports to HM Revenue and Customs in 2010-15.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","3542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384647","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK introduced legislation in Finance Bill 2015 in order to implement the G20-OECD model for Country-by-Country reporting. This will require multinational companies to provide information on the global allocation of income, economic activity and taxes, and will give tax authorities a clear picture of a multinational company’s global business, whilst ensuring the administrative costs for businesses are minimised.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OECD model for Country-by-Country reporting to tax authorities is for high level risk assessment purposes and includes protections to ensure sensitive information remains confidential. Making the reporting information public would not enhance risk assessment and would likely increase resource implications on both business and tax authorities. The UK has however transposed the EU Capital Requirements Directive IV, which requires public reporting for the banking and capital markets industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The European Commission has launched a public consultation on this issue and will evaluate the costs and benefits of different forms of Country-by-Country reporting, including the public disclosure of this information. The UK will be interested in understanding their findings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-25T15:17:11.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384647/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384647/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what mechanisms are in place to ensure that multinational enterprises publish full transparent breakdowns of their tax receipts.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","3543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384648","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>As announced when we issued the Invitation To Tender for the Northern franchise, we are committed to the removal of the existing Pacer trains by the end of 2019 at the latest. We are also requiring bidders to include in their fleet plans at least 120 new-build carriages, and to modernise all other trains operating on the Northern franchise.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T11:44:51.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384648/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384648/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to support rail and rolling stock replacement in the north east.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","3544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384649","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>No decisions have yet been made on the location or timing of HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) new Regional Centres. HMRC will be developing its plans over the coming months and will undertake all necessary consultations and impact assessment work to inform those plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","3602","2015-06-25T15:09:06.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384649/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384649/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment HM Revenue and Customs has made of the potential economic effect on Cumbernauld of moving its office there to a new regional West of Scotland campus in or around Glasgow, as proposed in Building our Future - Continuing the Conversation - Phase 2.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","3601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384650","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>No decisions have yet been made on the location or timing of HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) new Regional Centres. HMRC will be developing its plans over the coming months and will undertake all necessary consultations and impact assessment work to inform those plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","3601","2015-06-25T15:09:06.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384650/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384650/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what weight HM Revenue and Customs plans to give to the potential economic effect on towns where tax offices are sited of the establishment of regional centres under Building our Future - Continuing the Conversation - Phase 2 when making a decision on that programme.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","3602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384651","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-25","<p>Statistics on quarterly Right to Buy replacement starts of dwellings for each local authority district in England are published in the Department’s live table 693 here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales</a></p><p>The estimates of ‘replacement’ starts on site and acquisitions are a proxy for the number of replacement homes delivered using Right to Buy receipts.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-25T13:25:13.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384651/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384651/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the replacement rate of council homes sold through the right to buy scheme has been in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) nationally for each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384652","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-22","<p>Details of research reports commissioned between September 2010 and December 2014 are in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Department commissioned several reports on the ability to respond to major incidents, such as potential terrorist incidents, which were not intended for publication.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-07-22T16:25:19.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384652/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384652/answer","PQ 3580.xls","PQ 3580.xls","Table of Unpublished Data","Table of Unpublished Data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384652/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384652/answer/previousversion/9144","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Department for Communities and Local Government: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research reports his Department commissioned from external bodies between September 2010 and December 2014 have not been published; when each such report was commissioned; what the nature of the research commissioned for each such report was; from whom each such research report was commissioned; what the value of each such commission was; on what date each such report was received by his Department; for what reason each such report has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish each such report.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","3580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384653","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-25","<p>The 2015-16 Local Government Finance Settlement was approved by Parliament on 10 February 2015, and we have no plans to change this. <br><br>The closure of fire stations is a matter for Merseyside Fire Services to determine its own operational activities through its integrated risk management plan, in consultation with the local community.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-25T13:26:15.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384653/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384653/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Merseyside Fire and Rescue Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will review the Government's allocation of funding to Merseyside Fire and Rescue Authority and closure of the two fire stations in Wirral West constituency.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","3581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384654","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-30","<p>The objective of the Northern Powerhouse and the Government's long term economic plan is to rebalance growth across the regions and nations of the UK. Creating a Northern Powerhouse will enable the Northern Region to reach its potential as a driving force in the UK economy – adding a potential £44 billion to the Northern economy, or £1,600 per person living there (in real terms).</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-30T11:16:28.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384654/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384654/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the (a) policy objectives and (b) measurable outcomes are the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","3501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384655","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Government considers that energy performance standards for new homes are best set through the national building regulations which were strengthened in 2013. Councils play an important role in checking compliance with these standards.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-30T11:14:47.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384655/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384655/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to encourage councils to implement the zero-carbon home standard from 2016.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","3546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384656","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Department had four Non-Executive Directors in post before May 2015, all four remain in post. <br><br>The previous Secretary of State, my rt. hon. Friend the Member for Brentwood and Ongar (Eric Pickles), made six Non-Executive Director appointments to the Department since May 2010 - see attached table.<br><br></p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-30T11:13:35.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384656/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384656/answer","PQ 3552.docx","PQ 3552.docx","Table of Non-Exec Directors","Table of Non-Exec Directors","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384656/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Department for Communities and Local Government: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many non-executive directors of his Department who were in post before May 2015 have since left the Department's board; what the names and length of tenure of such directors were; and how many and what non-executive director appointments he has made since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","3552"
