use of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 596, how many UK supply chain (a) jobs and (b) apprenticeships were created by each type of renewable energy for each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","3569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384688","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Department does not hold a list detailing where components of the Rampion wind farm will be manufactured or which aspects of the supply chain will be UK manufactured.</p><p>However, recent announcements by EON have stated that: Carillion has been awarded a contract to design, supply and install 160km of 150kV cable and associated jointing accessories; Babcock International has won a contract to design, engineer and construct the 2500-tonne offshore substation platform topside and jacket; and the operations and maintenance building will be located in the port of Newhaven.</p><p>As mentioned in my previous answer, we are working closely with EON to ensure that UK supply chain companies have the opportunity to compete for contracts that have yet to be awarded.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-02T13:58:41.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384688/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384688/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 601, where components of the Rampion wind farm will be manufactured; and which aspects of the supply chain will be UK manufactured.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","3591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384689","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Government is working together with the Offshore Wind Industry to build a competitive and innovative UK supply chain that delivers and sustains jobs, exports and economic benefit for the UK.</p><p>Currently the offshore wind sector employs around 8,000 people directly, with a similar number of indirect jobs in the wider supply chain. With an investment opportunity of between £16bn - £21bn in the UK by 2020 plus export opportunities. Offshore wind has the potential to support tens of thousands of jobs and contribute billions to our economy.</p><p>The Department has not estimated the likely relative benefits for the supply chain in other countries of investment in off-shore wind.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-06T15:08:51.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384689/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384689/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 4 June 2015 to Question 603, what estimate she has made of the likely relative benefit for supply chains in (a) the UK and (b) other countries of investment in off-shore wind.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","3592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384690","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-26","<p>The generating capacity of wind turbines in Northamptonshire at the end of May 2015 was 91MW for operational turbines and 34.9MW for turbines with planning consent awaiting construction.</p><p>Source: Renewable Energy Planning Database (REPD), May 2015 extract:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-energy-planning-database-monthly-extract" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-energy-planning-database-monthly-extract</a></p><p><em>Please note:</em> the REPD captures projects entering planning that are 1MW or larger. Therefore, there may be additional onshore wind turbines not captured by the figures given above where these are smaller than 1MW.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-26T13:39:44.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384690/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384690/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the capacity is of wind turbines (a) built and (b) with planning consent awaiting construction in Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","3590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384691","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-25","<p>The costs of decommissioning onshore wind farms are met by developers of the projects in question. The consenting authority is able to include requirements for decommissioning and restoration of land to an acceptable condition as part of the planning approval process, which can include a requirement for developers to make adequate provisions to meet the costs of decommissioning a project.</p><p>Offshore, there is a statutory decommissioning scheme which allows the Secretary of State to compel wind farm developers to submit costed programmes for the removal of their projects with funds set aside for that purpose.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-25T13:06:59.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384691/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384691/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether there is any (a) local and (b) national Government support available for decommissioning wind farms at the end of their productive life span; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","3610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384692","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-25","<p>We have said that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3612","2015-06-25T13:06:07.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384692/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384692/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Morecambe and Lunesdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to her oral statement of 22 June 2015, HC Deb, column 618, on onshore wind subsidies, if she will publish a list of wind farms and turbine applications in Morecambe and Lunesdale constituency that can be appealed under the grace period.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","3611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384693","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-25","<p>We have said that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3611","2015-06-25T13:06:07.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384693/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384693/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power: Morecambe and Lunesdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to her oral statement of 22 June 2015, HC Deb, column 618, on onshore wind subsidies, if she will clarify the status of grace period and the proposed wind farm recently given planning permission on Heysham headlands port area; to what areas such a review would apply; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","3612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384694","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Government’s online planning practice guidance (<a href="http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/</a> ) includes information on the process for applications made for planning permission under the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Guidance on the process for projects that are nationally significant infrastructure projects under the Planning Act 2008 is also available online <a href="http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/application-process/" target="_blank">http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/application-process/</a> .</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are free to make links to this guidance on their own websites if they wish.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-25T14:27:04.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384694/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384694/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Energy: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ask or require local planning authorities to publish the planning routes for any application of (a) fracking and (b) any other energy facilities.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","3613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384695","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-26","<p>Nearly 90 per cent of all coal imported to the UK is steam coal, therefore figures for this type of coal are provided.</p><p>In the past ten years, over 90 per cent of UK steam coal imports originated from four countries: Russia, Colombia, the USA, and South Africa. Nearly half (49 per cent) of all coal imports in this period came from Russia. The table below gives UK steam coal imports by country from 2005 to 2014 in thousand tonnes:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>Country of Origin</em></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2005</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2006</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2007</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2008</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2009</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2010</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2011</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2012</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2013</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2014</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Russia</em></p></td><td><p>16,888</p></td><td><p>22,543</p></td><td><p>20,185</p></td><td><p>21,193</p></td><td><p>18,414</p></td><td><p>9,166</p></td><td><p>12,093</p></td><td><p>17,459</p></td><td><p>19,177</p></td><td><p>15,831</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Colombia</em></p></td><td><p>3,369</p></td><td><p>3,883</p></td><td><p>3,842</p></td><td><p>5,294</p></td><td><p>5,233</p></td><td><p>6,236</p></td><td><p>8,010</p></td><td><p>11,749</p></td><td><p>11,388</p></td><td><p>9,269</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>USA</em></p></td><td><p>266</p></td><td><p>707</p></td><td><p>1,121</p></td><td><p>2,792</p></td><td><p>3,112</p></td><td><p>2,349</p></td><td><p>4,461</p></td><td><p>8,858</p></td><td><p>9,528</p></td><td><p>7,687</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>EU (1)</em></p></td><td><p>1,001</p></td><td><p>1,584</p></td><td><p>482</p></td><td><p>933</p></td><td><p>1,136</p></td><td><p>881</p></td><