"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384202","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-01","<p>The total DFID programme spend in response to the humanitarian crises, arising from conflict in the Middle East, was £457 million in 2014–15. The budgeted cost for 2015–16 is £448 million. This money has been allocated to Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Iraq, Yemen, Libya, Egypt, Turkey and the Occupied Palestinian Territories.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-07-01T15:57:56.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384202/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384202/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-19","Middle East: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total cost during 2014–15, and what is the budgeted cost for 2015–16, of providing monetary assistance to persons displaced by conflict in the Middle East, and to which countries this money has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384204","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The perceived likelihood of illegal immigrants being able to remain in Europe after crossing the Mediterranean plays into the hands of the criminal gangs who are exploiting them. While the Government remains committed to saving lives at sea, it is clear that this link needs to be broken if the EU is to tackle the current situation successfully. That can be achieved only through concerted EU and international action, ensuring that Member States’ asylum systems are not exploited by people smugglers and traffickers or by economic migrants, and that those found not to be in need of protection are swiftly removed.</p><p>Ministers and officials are working closely with our counterparts in other European States and EU institutions to try to break this link, focusing on four key areas: conditions in migrants’ country of origin; availability of protection and economic opportunities in the region; tackling the criminal gangs; and ensuring the return of those who do not need to remain in the EU.</p><p>The UK is playing a leading role in practical EU efforts, including the development of joint work in transit and origin countries to combat people smugglers and traffickers and to enhance protection for those who genuinely require it.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-29T10:58:01.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384204/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384204/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-19","Refugees: Mediterranean Sea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to realise the Prime Minister's aim stated on 3 June, that "we need to break the link between getting on a boat and achieving residence in Europe" (HC Deb, col 583).","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384206","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Government agrees that decisions on the approval of pesticides should be based firmly on a scientific risk assessment. We take this position in EU negotiations on individual pesticide chemicals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The European Commission is due to review the rules for pesticide approval. The Government will make the case for changes that ensure that the legislation protects people and the environment on the basis of scientific evidence, without placing unwarranted barriers in the way of pesticide approval.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The European Commission’s Communication on application of the precautionary principle makes it clear that decisions should be based on the best possible scientific risk assessment and should be proportionate to the risk to be addressed. The Government supports this approach. We would not agree with the use of the term “precautionary principle” as cover for advocating a regulatory approach which is not backed by the scientific evidence.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-30T16:07:48.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384206/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384206/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Agriculture: Chemicals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that any proposals by the European Commission to ban an agricultural chemical are supported by full science-based risk analysis rather than the precautionary principle.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384208","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The previous Government made clear its commitment to working with other organisations to help deliver the best outcomes for offenders in its response to the independent review into the rehabilitation needs of ex-armed service personnel in the CJS by Stephen Phillips QC MP, in December 2014. The current Government shares this commitment and we will be issuing updated guidance for staff on working with ex-armed service personnel in custody and the community later this year.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T14:20:10.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384208/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384208/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-19","Prisoners: Veterans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have issued any guidelines to prison governors regarding the needs of prisoners who are veterans of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384340","Attorney General","false","2015-06-25","<p>No direct employees of the Government Legal Department (GLD) are paid less than the living wage. However, at 22 June 2015 GLD had four temporary workers in London receiving less than the living wage although this position will change after 12 weeks of engagement in line with the Agency Workers legislation. At that point, their salary will increase to a higher rate of pay comparable to the rate of a direct employee. All other temporary workers are paid more than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No direct employees or temporary workers employed by the remaining Law Officers' Departments are paid less than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p>A complete record on the pay arrangements for staff employed by companies contracted to provide services to the Law Officers' Departments is not held and could not be provided without incurring a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-25T15:25:09.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384340/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384340/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-19","Attorney General: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for the Law Officers' Departments and their subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384341","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-29","<p /> <p>A specific funding allocation has not been made.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-29T13:17:15.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384341/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384341/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-19","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2015 to Question 1895, what funding his Department has allocated to the review of consumer protection measures in the online secondary ticketing market.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384342","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-29","<p>There are no direct employees or agency staff in the core Department paid less than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p>We do not centrally hold details of the pay levels of staff working for outsourced companies contracted by the core Department.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked Chief Executives of the executive agencies to respond directly to the right Hon. Member.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-29T15:11:36.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384342/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384342/answer","agencies-response-pq-3306.pdf ; os-response-pq-3306.pdf","agencies-response-pq-3306.pdf ; os-response-pq-3306.pdf","BIS agencies response to the question ; Ordnance Survey response to the question","BIS agencies response to the question ; Ordnance Survey response to the question","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384342/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-19","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384343","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The statutory programme of study for citizenship includes how citizens can actively participate in the UK’s system of government and took effect in September 2014.</p><p>The Cabinet Office has, in partnership with youth organisations, developed learning resources, including Rock Enrol! which are available to download for free and can be used in schools to encourage young people to participate in democracy and register to vote.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-29T12:09:00.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384343/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384343/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-19","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to educate young people in secondary schools about electoral registration.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384344","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>Over £14 million has been invested over the last two financial years to support the cost of activities aimed at increasing the levels of voter registration, including in the run up to the General Election.</p><p>The Electoral Commission (EC) published on 18 June an analysis of the electoral registers used for the elections on 7 May. It showed that the numbers of entries on these registers had increased by 1% compared with the last ones published prior to the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration. The Government will keep under review its approach to electoral registration in light of the EC’s report and its findings.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-29T12:11:13.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384344/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384344/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-19","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to increase electoral registration in (a) London and (b) the rest of the UK.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384345","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Chancellor has announced a new National Living Wage compulsory as of next April, expected to reach £9 an hour by 2020. Tackling low pay is part of the Government's plan to move to a higher wage, lower tax and lower welfare society.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-10T08:24:42.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384345/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384345/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-19","Cabinet Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384346","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3333 ; 3344","2015-06-24T16:58:42.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384346/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384346/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the (a) age and (b) reliability of the nation's financial services' IT systems and risks represented to the nation's critical infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384347","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3333 ; 3352","2015-06-24T16:58:42.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384347/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384347/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the state of the financial service sector's IT systems is recorded on any risk register.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384348","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>Responsibility for information technology infrastructure in the UK financial sector is primarily for the firms themselves. However, the Financial Authorities have a role to play in supervising, coordinating and driving change to improve the operational resilience of the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) jointly launched, in October 2014, a review of firms’ critical infrastructure and technology resilience. The review focuses on the most significant UK retail deposit-taking organisations and is expected to conclude later this summer. The results will not be published but the FCA and PRA will provide feedback to the firms individually on their findings and any follow-up actions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The risk of a bank experiencing severe and prolonged technical problems affecting its core infrastructure is included as an example of technical failure in the 2015 edition of the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published by the Cabinet Office and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-risk-register-for-civil-emergencies-2015-edition</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3344 ; 3352","2015-06-24T16:58:42.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384348/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384348/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Financial Services: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the financial industry on the state of the financial services sector's IT systems.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384349","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government’s shareholding in Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is managed at arm’s length from HM Treasury by UK Financial Investments (UKFI). UKFI is responsible for managing the Government’s shareholding, as well as devising and executing any sales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The management of RBS Group is responsible for the commercial operation of its banks, rather than the administration of the Government’s shareholding or any of its potential disposal options.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-24T13:33:15.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384349/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384349/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons he did not discuss the sale of the Government's shareholding in Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) Group with RBS, NatWest Bank or Ulster Bank; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384350","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is a commercial company in which the Government is a currently a shareholder. The Government’s shareholdings are managed on an arm’s length basis by UK Financial Investments (UKFI). UKFI’s role is to manage the shareholdings, not to manage the bank.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government created a new, tough City regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), to protect customers and ensure Britain’s banks conduct themselves to the highest standards. Irrespective of shareholder makeup, and in common with all UK banks, RBS is subject to the FCA’s Banking Conduct Regime, which covers the treatment of customers. RBS is required to fully comply with this regime going forward.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-24T13:32:24.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384350/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384350/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to ensure that the sale of the Government's shareholding in Royal Bank of Scotland Group does not have detrimental financial implications for customers of the banks in that group.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384351","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Chancellor keeps all taxes under review and considers them in the round. This means carefully considering their impact on industries such as tourism and on regional economies, as well as their contribution to the public finances and the efforts of the Government to reduce the deficit.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Air passenger duty makes an important contribution to deficit reduction. Nevertheless, the Government has exempted children from APD and reduced rates on the longest-haul flights. This will help enhance the competitiveness of the UK tourism industry and reduce the cost of holidays for families.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-06-24T16:07:14.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384351/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384351/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of reducing air passenger duty on tourism, visitor numbers and regional economies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384352","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government remains committed to bringing forward Tax-Free Childcare to help working families. The Chancellor of the Exchequer will set out the timing of the introduction as part of his Budget.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","3298 ; 3299","2015-06-24T16:55:17.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384352/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384352/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to roll out tax-free childcare over 12 months from autumn 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","3350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384353","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-29","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5">No direct employees of HM Treasury and its agencies, are paid less than the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation as a living wage. <br><br>The Government awards contracts on the basis of the best value for money for taxpayers.<br><br>HM Treasury does not hold information on wages paid by our suppliers.</td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-29T13:53:19.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384353/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384353/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Treasury: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384354","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government remains committed to bringing forward Tax-Free Childcare to help working families. The Chancellor of the Exchequer will set out the timing of the introduction as part of his Budget.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","3299 ; 3350","2015-06-24T16:55:17.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384354/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384354/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Children: Daycare","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress National Savings and Investments (NS&I) has made on developing the IT infrastructure that will underpin tax-free childcare; and whether NS&I expect that system to be ready to begin taking registration from parents in autumn 2015.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","3298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384355","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government remains committed to bringing forward Tax-Free Childcare to help working families. The Chancellor of the Exchequer will set out the timing of the introduction as part of his Budget.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","3298 ; 3350","2015-06-24T16:55:17.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384355/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384355/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-19","Children: Daycare","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects parents to begin opening online accounts under the new tax-free childcare scheme; and when he expects eligible parents to receive top-up payments.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","3299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384356","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-29","<p>My Department and its subsidiary agencies, with one exception, have no direct employees or agency staff earning less than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p>One of our non-departmental public bodies, the Homes and Communities Agency, has 13 outsourced staff paid less than the living wage, all based outside London.</p><p> </p><p>70 support staff employed by Interserve (who provides facilities management services to the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department for Education) are paid less than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working with Interserve to see if contract efficiencies can be secured to help them voluntarily pay the living wage to all staff working on the Department’s facilities management contract.</p><p> </p><p>The Department maintains a position that the level of employee payment is for our external contractors to determine, while encouraging payment of a living wage.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-29T16:20:20.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384356/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384356/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Department for Communities and Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384357","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Civil Contingencies Act 2004 and the Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004 detail the roles and powers of fire and rescue authorities in respect of both emergency response and rescue in a wide range of situations, including from flooding. Fire and rescue authorities are expected to produce Integrated Risk Management Plans which identify the full range of risks that an authority’s service is expected to respond to and is subject to consultation. This approach is enshrined in the National Fire Framework which was given statutory effect in August 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-29T16:25:05.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384357/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384357/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Fire Services: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will bring forward legislative proposals to introduce a statutory duty for the fire and rescue service to respond to a major flooding incident; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","3341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384358","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>We do not hold the information requested.<br><br>However no public money is used to subsidise private landlords through Help to Buy as once a property is sold on, any assistance given to the initial purchase comes to an end.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","3335","2015-06-24T11:30:37.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384358/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384358/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of properties bought under the help to buy scheme that have since been sold to private sector landlords.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","3334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384359","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>We do not hold the information requested.<br><br>However no public money is used to subsidise private landlords through Help to Buy as once a property is sold on, any assistance given to the initial purchase comes to an end.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","3334","2015-06-24T11:30:36.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384359/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384359/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of properties bought under the help to buy scheme in each (a) constituency and (b) local authority area are now rented.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","3335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384360","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government's letter of 27 March (available on the Government's website at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/letter-to-the-chief-executive-of-the-planning-inspectorate) summarised the Government's policy in respect of landscape character and prematurity. <br><br>Those policies are set out in full in the Government's National Planning Policy Framework and supported by planning guidance. <br><br>I would reiterate that the Government's policy retains strong protections against inappropriate development in valued areas even in the absence of an adopted and up-to-date Local Plan. Paragraph 211 of the Framework makes clear that policies in Local Plans should not be considered out-of-date simply because they were adopted prior to the publication of this Framework.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-24T15:07:29.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384360/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384360/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the letter of 27 March 2015 from the Minister of State for Housing and Planning to the Chief Executive of the Planning Inspectorate, what his policy is on landscape character and prematurity in planning decisions.","false","Biography information for Nick Herbert","Arundel and South Downs","Nick Herbert","3336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384361","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>The written statement of 25 March, <em>Official Report</em>, HCWS488 is the most up to date expression of planning policy for solar energy developments and should be read alongside the National Planning Policy Framework and relevant planning practice guidance, which can be found at the following link:</p><p><br>http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-24T11:26:49.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384361/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384361/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Written Statement of 25 March 2015, HCW488 what his policy is on solar energy.","false","Biography information for Nick Herbert","Arundel and South Downs","Nick Herbert","3337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384362","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>Paragraph 52 of our National Planning Policy Framework recognises that the supply of new homes can sometimes be best achieved through planning for larger scale development such as new settlements. However it also clearly sets out that all areas should prepare a Local Plan, which, as far as possible, represents a collective vision and set of agreed priorities for the area. <br><br>Decisions on particular proposals must be taken in line with the Local Plan unless material considerations indicate otherwise.<br><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-24T11:29:05.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384362/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384362/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-19","New Towns","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's policy is on proposals by developers to build new towns that do not accord with local plans.","false","Biography information for Nick Herbert","Arundel and South Downs","Nick Herbert","3338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384363","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-26","<p>Employment levels in the local newspaper industry have been discussed at a number of summits and meetings my department has held with the local newspaper industry. These discussions have indicated there has been a steady decline in employment figures in the local newspaper industry since 2010.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-26T10:20:12.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384363/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384363/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Local press: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of trends in the levels of employment in the local newspaper industry since 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","3346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384364","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>UK Government are not organising a memorial however the Sikh community have plans in place to unveil a permanent memorial at the National Memorial Arboretum in Staffordshire in the autumn.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-29T14:40:25.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384364/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384364/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","World War I: Sikhs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department is making on determining a permanent memorial to mark the Sikh contribution to the First World War.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","3351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384365","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>The annual library statistics compiled and published, in December each year, by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy indicate that the number of libraries open for 10 hours or more a week in England at 31 March for the years requested is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>31 March</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Public Libraries Open 10+ Hours per week</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,428</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,397</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,243</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,181</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,142</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We are not able to estimate the cost of collecting information on the number of volunteer-run libraries now and on an on-going basis.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T13:20:08.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384365/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384365/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 June 2015 to Question 613, how many libraries were open for 10 hours or more a week in each year between 2010 and 2015; if he will estimate the cost of collecting information on the number of volunteer-run libraries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384366","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The list of all libraries which our research indicates do not currently have WiFi is checked and updated on a regular basis. It would be impractical to place such an ephemeral document in the House Library.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-29T15:08:10.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384366/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384366/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 June 2015 to Question 614, on libraries: wi-fi, if he will place in the Library a list of all libraries which his Department's current desktop research indicates do not currently have wi-fi, together with information on which local authority has responsibility for each.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384367","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>Discussions about the creation of a new Cultural Protection Fund have taken place within Government and with key cultural organisations who agree that this measure is needed. These discussions will continue as work to develop the fund progresses.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T13:22:11.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384367/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384367/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Cultural Heritage: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2015 to Question 1896, what representations he has received about creating a cultural protection fund; and what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on such a fund.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384368","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Further to my answer of 4 June 2015 to Question 614, the scheme is due to run until 31 March 2016.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-29T15:06:29.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384368/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384368/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 June 2015 to Question 614, on libraries: wi-fi,  when Arts Council England plans to finish the scheme.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384369","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>I refer the Hon. Gentleman to my answer of 26 June 2015 (HC3211). All employees within the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, its agency workers and outsourced employees are paid above the living wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold data for its Arm’s length bodies.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-29T15:12:11.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384369/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384369/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384370","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The secondary ticketing provisions in the Consumer Rights Act came into force on 26 May 2015.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-29T16:33:45.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384370/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384370/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Consumer Rights Act 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2015 to Question 1895, what the commencement dates are of the relevant aspects of the Consumer Rights Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384371","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-26","<p>We are working with the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Treasury. Department for Culture, Media and Sport ministers have not met with their counterparts to discuss this issue specifically as it has been dealt with at official level.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-26T10:18:40.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384371/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384371/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Non-domestic Rates: Local Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 617, on non domestic rates: local areas, which other departments his Department is working with; and on what dates Ministers in his Department have had discussions on this issue with their counterparts in other departments.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384372","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>Superfast broadband availability across the UK is approximately 80%, up from 45% in 2010. According to Ofcom, the proportion of connections that are superfast has increased year on year, whilst the total number of broadband connections (standard &amp; superfast) has also steadily increased with over 22.8 million fixed broadband connections in March 2014. The proportion of broadband connections that have speeds of above 30Mbps was 32% in November 2014, up from 1% in November 2010.</p><p>This lag is in line with the take-up of many new technologies.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T16:28:32.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384372/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384372/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Broadband: Business Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2015 to Question 611, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the difference between the number of premises with access to superfast broadband and the number of premises using such broadband; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384373","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport plan to publish the 2014-15 Annual Report and Accounts in mid-July i.e. before Parliament rises for the summer recess (3 1/2 months earlier than the 2013-14 Annual Report and Accounts).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T09:36:42.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384373/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384373/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Annual Reports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish his Department's Annual Report and Accounts.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384374","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>There are 13 FTE officials working on BBC related matters, which includes Charter Review, supporting the TV Licence Fee Enforcement Review and other work relating to the BBC.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T14:24:34.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384374/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384374/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many full-time equivalent officials are working on Charter Renewal.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384375","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>DCMS directly provides grant-in-aid funding to 15 museums and galleries and the British Library. These Museums hold their collections in trust for the nation. Museum collections are inalienable in their nature and no overall assessment of their value is made. The historical value of objects acquired since 2002 is disclosed in individual museum reports and accounts. This is not split between items on display and items in storage.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T16:29:50.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384375/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384375/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Museums and Galleries: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the value is of arts assets in the vaults of the museums and galleries which receive grant-in-aid.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384376","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>£7.1m from the £7.4m has been allocated as capital costs, the remaining £0.3m is administrative costs to manage the grant scheme. The estimated figures for the average installation and on-going costs for WiFi will be included in the project specification which will be published at the launch of the scheme in July.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T14:23:41.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384376/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384376/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 June 215 to Question 614, whether the £7.4 million being made available to help all public libraries to install wi-fi is only for the capital cost of installation; what estimate he has made of the average cost of installing wi-fi; and what estimate has he made of the non-capital costs over each of the next five years of providing free wi-fi in the libraries that do not have it.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384377","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-26","<p>We do not have annual statistics showing the number of operational local newspapers. According to the News Media Association, there has been an overall decline from 1212 local newspapers in 2010 to 1065 in 2015. We have not made any official estimate of the number of such newspapers in any future years.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-26T10:21:13.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384377/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384377/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-19","Local press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many local and regional newspapers there were in each of the last five years; whether he has estimated the (a) numbers of such newspapers in any future years and (b) trends in that number; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384378","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-29","<p>The information requested is shown below. Contracted workers' rates of pay, where paid by their parent company or recruitment agency, are not visible to the Ministry of Defence (MOD).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>London</strong> <strong>Living Wage (£9.15 per hour)</strong></p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>MOD (London)</p></td><td><p>39</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>National Living Wage (£7.85 per hour)</strong></p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>MOD (outside London)</p></td><td><p>1,159</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Defence Science &amp; Technology Laboratory</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>United Kingdom Hydrographic Office</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Defence Electronics and Components Agency</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-29T15:31:43.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384378/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384378/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-19","Ministry of Defence: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384379","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Department for Education and its executive agencies have no directly employed staff paid below the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department has 14 temporary agency staff currently receiving a rate below the living wage, but who will shortly move to arrangements which ensure they are paid at least this rate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>External contractors who provide facilities management services to the Department have confirmed that they have 108 staff paid under the living wage rate. This is a reduction from 146 staff in October 2014.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-25T13:11:11.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384379/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384379/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-19","Department for Education: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384380","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-26","<p>Onshore wind has made a valuable contribution to the UK energy mix in recent years but there is now enough capacity in the pipeline to help the UK meet its 2020 renewable commitments. We will consider carefully the level of investment that developers are likely to bring forward under the proposals announced by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 18th June.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-26T13:38:36.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384380/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384380/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-19","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make an assessment of the effect of the removal of the Renewables Obligation from onshore wind in 2016 on investor confidence in renewable energy in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384381","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Department has no staff who are paid less than the London or National Living Wage.</p><p>DECC has received assurances from its key suppliers that they have no workers currently in post earning less than the London or National Living Wage guidelines.</p><p>DECC is also signed into a larger Shared Services contract through the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs (Defra) to provide Facilities Management (FM) and Catering services. There are 21 staff working for the FM contractor &amp; 6 working for the catering contractor who receive less than the London Living Wage and are based primarily in DECC buildings. DECC is also signed into a larger Shared Services contract through the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs (Defra) to provide Facilities Management (FM) and Catering services. There are 21 staff working for the FM contractor &amp; 6 working for the catering contractor who receive less than the London Living Wage and are based primarily in DECC buildings.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-26T13:36:27.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384381/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384381/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-19","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384382","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>For the core department and its executive agencies, the number of people currently employed on less than the living wage is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(a) As at 1 April 2015, all permanent staff are paid above the living wage. There are 7 apprentices paid below the Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(b) 66 agency (temporary) staff are paid below the Living Wage;</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(c) As at December 2014, 253 outsourced staff, employed by contractors with the central Department to provide office and building services in the central Department and its agencies, were paid below the Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-29T16:57:51.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384382/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384382/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384383","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Defra has not made an assessment of the security of supply of potash minerals. The UK currently has one domestic mine for supply and therefore depends on some imports. Import statistics provided to Defra by the Agriculture Industries Confederation show that 135,000 tonnes of straight potash fertilisers and 389,000 tonnes of potash-containing compound fertilisers were imported into the UK from a wide range of EU and non-EU countries in the 12 months to March 2015 making up approximately 40% of UK consumption.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-24T14:15:59.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384383/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384383/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Potash","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the need for security of supply of potash minerals.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","3328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384384","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Defra is working with the Beak Trimming Action Group, to find ways to manage laying hens without the need to beak trim. As part of this process, Defra has funded a study at the University of Bristol to assess the effectiveness of management strategies in reducing injurious pecking in non-beak trimmed laying hens. A review of all the evidence, including the outcome of the Bristol study, will be carried out later this year.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","3305","2015-06-24T12:08:18.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384384/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384384/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Poultry: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on beak trimming of chickens; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384385","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Defra is working with the Beak Trimming Action Group, to find ways to manage laying hens without the need to beak trim. As part of this process, Defra has funded a study at the University of Bristol to assess the effectiveness of management strategies in reducing injurious pecking in non-beak trimmed laying hens. A review of all the evidence, including the outcome of the Bristol study, will be carried out later this year.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","3279","2015-06-24T12:08:18.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384385/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384385/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Birds: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made on research on non-beak trimmed birds; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384386","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Defra has not discussed the impact seals have on fish stocks, the control of seal populations to maintain fish stocks or improving the level of protection offered to seals with the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue. In England, the Conservation of Seals Act 1970 strikes a proportionate balance between the conservation and welfare of the seals and the needs of those impacted by individual problem seals. We have no plans to review this legislative protection. There is no evidence to suggest that the limited local control of seals permitted in England is having an adverse effect on the conservation status of the UK seal population as a whole.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-24T16:48:51.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384386/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384386/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Seals: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Scottish Government on (a) the effects of seals on fishing populations, (b) minimising the need to kill seals to maintain fishing populations and (c) improving the level of protection for seals.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384387","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>Fisheries management does take account of seal predation. Scientists include estimates of seal predation in annual stock assessments where appropriate. These assessments inform the amount of fish which can be sustainably removed each year by the fishing industry. Seals are also known to interact with fishing gear and work on how to limit these interactions is ongoing.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-29T15:40:15.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384387/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384387/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Seals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect seals have on (a) fish populations and (b) fishing equipment.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384388","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given to the Rt Hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne East (Rt Hon Nick Brown) on 15 June 2015, PQ 1799.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-24T16:51:36.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384388/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384388/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-19","Seals: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department has taken to improve protection for the seal population.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384389","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>No direct employees of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) are paid less than the living wage.</p><p>Agency Workers are engaged through a managed service contract. The minimum hourly rates paid are greater than the Living Wage.</p><p>A complete record on the pay arrangements for staff employed by companies contracted to provide services to the FCO is not held centrally.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-29T15:27:32.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384389/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384389/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-19","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384390","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>No civil servants employed by the ‘core’ Department or its executive agencies: Public Health England and the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency are paid less than the Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In line with Cabinet Office advice, the Department and its executive agencies do not require their contracted companies to pay their employees the local Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Currently, for agency staff (agency temps and contractors) working with the ‘core’ Department, six individual agency staff earn under the London Living Wage and one individual (an apprentice) earns under the National Living Wage. These are out of a total of 50 agency staff employed by the ‘core’ Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Similarly, the Department and its executive agencies have outsourced service providers on their premises that are also obliged to pay the National Minimum Wage but not obliged to pay the Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Currently, staff working for outsourced service provider Compass number 34 individuals working in London on the Department’s catering contract, none of whom are paid below London Living Wage levels.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Currently, the number of staff working for outsourced service provider EMCOR who earn below London Living Wage is 109. EMCOR does not provide services to the Department outside the London area.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-29T16:01:26.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384390/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384390/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Department of Health: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384391","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>Strategic Clinical Networks admin funding is allocated on an equal share basis. Programme funding is allocated on an un-weighted population basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013/14 and 2014/15 funding allocations covered both Strategic Clinical Networks and Clinical Senates. In 2015/16, funding for Strategic Clinical Networks has been separated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For both 2013/14 and 2014/15, the allocations were:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Geographical Area</p><p>(Strategic Clinical Network and Clinical Senate)</p></td><td><p>Admin Funding £’000</p></td><td><p>Programme Funding £’000</p></td><td><p>TOTAL</p><p>£’000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheshire and Merseyside</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,447</p></td><td><p>£2,281</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,573</p></td><td><p>£4,406</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,825</p></td><td><p>£3,658</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester, Lancashire and South Cumbria</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,606</p></td><td><p>£3,439</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern England</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,879</p></td><td><p>£2,712</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£4,794</p></td><td><p>£5,627</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,687</p></td><td><p>£3,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,793</p></td><td><p>£3,626</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thames Valley</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,233</p></td><td><p>£2,066</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wessex</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,592</p></td><td><p>£2,426</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,342</p></td><td><p>£4,175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,230</p></td><td><p>£4,063</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>£10 million</p></td><td><p>£32 million</p></td><td><p>£42 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong>The 2015/16 programme budget allocations for Clinical Networks were:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Clinical Network</p></td><td><p>2015/16 Programme Funding</p><p>£’000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheshire and Mersey</p></td><td><p>£1,059</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£2,725</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£2,043</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester, Lancashire and South Cumbria</p></td><td><p>£1,968</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern England</p></td><td><p>£1,438</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£3,633</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£2,043</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£2,119</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thames Valley</p></td><td><p>£1,059</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wessex</p></td><td><p>£1,211</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£2,573</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>£2,422</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>£24.3 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The admin funding for Clinical Networks in 2015/16 is currently being determined as part of the implementation of NHS England’s Organisational Alignment and Capability Programme.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","3353","2015-06-29T15:46:13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384391/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384391/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Strategic Clinical Networks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what criteria are used to allocate budgets to each NHS Strategic Clinical Network.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","3277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384392","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>Data on waiting times to see a general practitioner are not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-29T15:20:46.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384392/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384392/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust: General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients in the Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust had to wait longer than 48 hours for a GP appointment in (a) 2010 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384393","Department of Health","false","2015-06-24","<p>Mental health research spend data is not available for 2000/01 and 2001/02.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Estimated spend on mental health from research and development (R&amp;D) allocations to National Health Service organisations in the period from 2002/03 to 2004/05 is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p><em>£ million</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002/03</p></td><td><p>45.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003/04</p></td><td><p>48.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>51.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data is not available for this period for spend on mental health by the Department’s centrally managed research programmes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows estimated spend on mental health from the NHS R&amp;D / National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) revenue budget, and this spend as a proportion of total expenditure from this budget.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS R&amp;D / NIHR estimated spend on mental health</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p> </p><p><em>£ million</em></p></td><td><p>Proportion of NHS R&amp;D / NIHR budget</p><p><em>%</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>59.8</p></td><td><p>9.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>64.0</p></td><td><p>9.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>65.6</p></td><td><p>9.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>67.9</p></td><td><p>8.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>From 2009/10, spend on research funded directly by the NIHR has been categorised by Health Research Classification System (HRCS) health categories. NIHR expenditure on research infrastructure and systems where spend cannot be attributed to health categories is excluded. The following table shows NIHR spend in the ‘mental health’ category, and this spend as a proportion of total categorised spend and as a proportion of total revenue expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td colspan="3"><p>NIHR spend in ‘mental health’ HRCS health category</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p><p><em>£ million</em></p></td><td><p>Proportion of total categorised NIHR spend</p><p><em>%</em></p></td><td><p>Proportion of total NIHR revenue spend</p><p><em>%</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>40.3</p></td><td><p>7.9</p></td><td><p>4.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>49.8</p></td><td><p>9.0</p></td><td><p>5.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>53.2</p></td><td><p>9.0</p></td><td><p>5.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>70.0</p></td><td><p>9.5</p></td><td><p>7.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>71.7</p></td><td><p>9.5</p></td><td><p>7.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NIHR data for 2014/15 spend in mental health is not yet available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Department commissions research through the Policy Research Programme (PRP) which funds research to inform policy development and implementation across the full range of the Department’s responsibilities. Spend on research funded directly by the PRP in mental health is available for the period from 2010/11 to 2013/14 and is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p><em>£ million</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>1.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>0.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Department’s expenditure from central R&amp;D revenue budgets is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p>NHS R&amp;D / NIHR</p><p><em>£ million</em></p></td><td><p>PRP</p><p><em>£ million</em></p></td><td><p>TOTAL</p><p><em>£ million</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000/01</p></td><td><p>448</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>482</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001/02</p></td><td><p>475</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>510</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002/03</p></td><td><p>506</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003/04</p></td><td><p>533</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>565</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>601</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>631</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>617</p></td><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>646</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>662</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>693</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>735</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>763</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>788</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>825</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>851</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>885</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>920</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>960</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>921</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>952</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>955</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>985</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>987</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>1,018</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Prior to the establishment of the NIHR in April 2006, the main part of the Department’s total health research expenditure was devolved to and managed by NHS organisations. The NHS organisations reported on their use of these allocations in annual R&amp;D reports. These reports estimated total, aggregated spend on certain priority areas including mental health. Where a research project related to two or more priority areas, the expenditure on it was included within each relevant area. From April 2006 to March 2009, transitional research funding was allocated to these organisations at reducing levels. At the same time, an increasing amount of NHS research funding was awarded competitively through new NIHR programmes and schemes.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-24T15:56:17.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384393/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384393/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funds his Department has provided for mental health research (a) in cash terms, (b) in real terms and (c) as a proportion of the total research and development budget in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384394","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>People in close contact with a prisoner diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) in HMP &amp; YOI Swinfen Hall in October 2014, during the period of time when the prisoner was infectious, were identified, assessed and offered testing for signs of infection.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Collaborative work between the National Offender Management Service and Public Health England (PHE) allowed the identification of 49 individuals who were subsequently transferred to another prison, as well as 32 released back to the community. Testing and follow up of individuals continues and has been coordinated between PHE centres and local TB services in their area of residence.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-29T14:41:08.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384394/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384394/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Swinfen Hall Prison: Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether individuals who were released from Young Offender Institution Swinfen Hall since October 2014 have been identified and screened for tuberculosis.","false","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher","3276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384395","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>An investigation led by Public Health England was undertaken at HMP &amp; YOI Swinfen Hall into the possibility that a case of pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) diagnosed in a prisoner in October 2014 was epidemiologically linked to three cases subsequently diagnosed during 2015. The outcome of the investigation has suggested that the cases could be linked, which has informed subsequent contact screening, and on-going efforts on raising awareness and early recognition of TB symptoms not only in this prison, but across the prison estate especially those receiving transfers from HMP &amp; YOI Swinfen Hall.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-29T14:44:39.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384395/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384395/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Swinfen Hall Prison: Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the case of tuberculosis diagnosed at Young Offender Institution Swinfen Hall in October 2014 is directly linked to the three cases identified at the same site between March and May 2015.","false","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher","3304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384396","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Impact Assessment for funding reform to care and support sets out the costs and benefits of the reforms and was last updated in February 2013 to support the consultation on draft regulations and guidance. A final Impact Assessment will be published alongside the final regulations and guidance.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-29T15:17:25.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384396/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384396/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will update its impact assessment for funding reform to care and support services in England to take account of the Government's policy to increase inheritance tax thresholds by 2020.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","3345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384397","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>Strategic Clinical Networks admin funding is allocated on an equal share basis. Programme funding is allocated on an un-weighted population basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013/14 and 2014/15 funding allocations covered both Strategic Clinical Networks and Clinical Senates. In 2015/16, funding for Strategic Clinical Networks has been separated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For both 2013/14 and 2014/15, the allocations were:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Geographical Area</p><p>(Strategic Clinical Network and Clinical Senate)</p></td><td><p>Admin Funding £’000</p></td><td><p>Programme Funding £’000</p></td><td><p>TOTAL</p><p>£’000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheshire and Merseyside</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,447</p></td><td><p>£2,281</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,573</p></td><td><p>£4,406</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,825</p></td><td><p>£3,658</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester, Lancashire and South Cumbria</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,606</p></td><td><p>£3,439</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern England</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,879</p></td><td><p>£2,712</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£4,794</p></td><td><p>£5,627</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,687</p></td><td><p>£3,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£2,793</p></td><td><p>£3,626</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thames Valley</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,233</p></td><td><p>£2,066</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wessex</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£1,592</p></td><td><p>£2,426</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,342</p></td><td><p>£4,175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>£833</p></td><td><p>£3,230</p></td><td><p>£4,063</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>£10 million</p></td><td><p>£32 million</p></td><td><p>£42 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong>The 2015/16 programme budget allocations for Clinical Networks were:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Clinical Network</p></td><td><p>2015/16 Programme Funding</p><p>£’000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheshire and Mersey</p></td><td><p>£1,059</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£2,725</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£2,043</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester, Lancashire and South Cumbria</p></td><td><p>£1,968</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern England</p></td><td><p>£1,438</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£3,633</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£2,043</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£2,119</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thames Valley</p></td><td><p>£1,059</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wessex</p></td><td><p>£1,211</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£2,573</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>£2,422</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>£24.3 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The admin funding for Clinical Networks in 2015/16 is currently being determined as part of the implementation of NHS England’s Organisational Alignment and Capability Programme.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","3277","2015-06-29T15:46:13.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384397/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384397/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-19","Strategic Clinical Networks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what budget has been allocated to each NHS Strategic Clinical Network in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","3353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384398","Home Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The most recent figures available from 1 April 2014 to 31 March 2015 show A) the number of Entry Clearance applications made via the Visa Application Centre in Erbil, Iraq to be 2,895 and B) the number of refusals 1,600.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-25T15:48:28.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384398/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384398/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-19","Entry Clearances: Iraq","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from the Kurdistan Region in Iraq (a) applied for and (b) were refused entry clearance to the UK in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","3343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384399","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Home Office produced an Impact Assessment in respect of its reforms of student routes in June 2011, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257825/ia-students-.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257825/ia-students-.pdf</a></p><p>We closed the Tier 1 (Post Study Work) route in 2012 because too many individuals in the route were unemployed or in low-skilled work, and too many were using the student route merely as a means to work in the UK, without any intention of study.</p><p>Under the current provisions, there is no limit on the number of genuine students who can come to the UK. Nor is there a limit on the number of graduates who can remain in the UK after their studies. All that non-EEA graduates of UK universities require to stay on to work is a graduate level job with an appropriate salary and an employer who is a Tier 2 sponsor.</p><p>The number of non-EU domiciled students enrolling at Scottish higher education institutions has not declined: in 2013/14 it was 28,610, compared with 28,500 in 2011/12.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-29T14:36:48.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384399/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384399/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-19","Overseas Students: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has made of the economic effect on universities in Scotland of the removal of the post-study work visa.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384400","Home Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>All permanent members of staff directly employed by the Home Office are paid the Living Wage or above.</p><p>All temporary agency staff are employed in accordance with the Agency Workers Regulations which ensures parity with directly employed staff after 12 weeks.</p><p>The Home Office only keeps information on the legal minimum standards of pay of staff employed by organisations contracted to provide services within the Home Office, not the living wage.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-06-24T14:30:14.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384400/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384400/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384400/answer/previousversion/7796","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-19","Home Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384401","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p><strong>Direct employees</strong></p><p>There are no staff directly employed by DFID who are paid less than the National or London Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Agency staff</strong></p><p>None of the agencies which DFID uses to engage temporary staff pay less than the National or London Living wage.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Outsourced workers</strong></p><p>DFID considers the rate of pay for outsourced workers to be an issue for contractors. We encourage outsource partners to pay the National or London Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-25T16:36:24.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384401/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384401/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-19","Department for International Development: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384402","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK Government takes comprehensive measures to ensure that the projects it funds in Gaza do not breach European Union or UK counter terror legislation. We continue to take extensive precautions to ensure that Hamas does not derive any financial benefit from our projects, including by providing £0.5m to support the Materials Monitoring Unit (MMU) which oversees and monitors the import, storage, supply and use of construction materials into Gaza through the Gaza Reconstruction Mechanism.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-25T16:34:39.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384402/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384402/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-19","Hamas: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the use by Hamas of (a) UK and (b) UN humanitarian aid.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384403","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-29","<p>DFID takes any allegation of mistreatment seriously and where there is firm evidence of abuse we will take immediate action. Assessing the environmental, social and governance (ESG) safeguard standards is critical for investments in private entities. In this case, we reviewed the systems that our intermediary put in place to assess the standards and practices of their investment. Our initial findings are that the intermediary through which DFID funds flowed applied International Finance Corporation safeguard standards and found that Agrica had complied with them.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-29T16:19:31.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384403/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384403/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-19","Tanzania: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her Department's policies of the findings of Irresponsible Investment: Agrica's broken development model in Tanzania, published on 17 June 2015 by Global Justice Now, the Oakland Institute and Greenpeace Africa.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","3347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384404","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-29","<p>Further to my answer at Ministry of Justice Orals on 23 June 2015, all civil servants within the Ministry of Justice and its agencies excluding the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) were paid above the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation as a living wage on 1 August 2014.</p><p> </p><p>As of 31 March 2015, after the Foundation increased the rate in November 2014, 283 staff out of 23,598 direct employees within the Ministry of Justice HQ, HM Courts and Tribunal Service, Office of the Public Guardian and Legal Aid Agency were paid below the current living wage.</p><p> </p><p>As of 31 March 2015, there were 89 members of staff who currently earn below the living wage out of a total of 46,442 direct employees in NOMS (including the National Probation Service).</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State would like all MoJ staff to be paid at least the current living wage. The department is working to implement this as soon as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Information on contractors paid less than the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation as a living wage is not recorded centrally.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-06-29T09:27:44.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384404/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384404/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-19","Ministry of Justice: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384405","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>My Department does not directly employ any members of staff on an hourly rate below that set by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p>In my Department’s Belfast office, there are 12 staff working for companies contracted by the Department. Of these staff, 11 are paid less than the hourly Living Wage set by the Living Wage Foundation for employees outside London, but are paid above the minimum wage.</p><p>My Department’s London office does not have any direct contracts with companies. All staff such as cleaners are provided by the building management company with whom we have a lease and arrangement to provide such services.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-25T16:23:11.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384405/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384405/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-19","Northern Ireland Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for her Department are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384406","Prime Minister","false","2015-06-25","<p>Implementation task forces will meet as and when required. Their membership has already been published on the Cabinet Office website and is available in the Library of the House. The Cabinet Secretariat and officials from across Whitehall will support the work of the task forces. Publication of minutes will follow the same approach as successive administrations for cabinet committees.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-06-25T15:24:37.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384406/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384406/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-06-19","Task Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when the (a) Earn or Learn and (b) Digital infrastructure and inclusion implementation taskforces will meet; who will participate in those meetings; when minutes of these meetings will be published; whether those minutes will list attendees; whether the taskforces have secretariats; what resources are assigned to the taskforces; and how many full-time equivalent officials work on those taskforces.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384407","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. All staff that join the Scotland Office do so on assignment, secondment or loan agreement from other Government bodies. All staff on such arrangements are paid more than the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p>The Scotland Office has one contract which provides security for the office in Edinburgh. The Scotland Office does not set the wages paid by the contractors to its workers; however, the wage paid by the contractor is above the National Minimum Wage. Otherwise, the Scotland Office uses framework contracts for building services held by the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-25T14:11:13.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384407/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384407/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-19","Scotland Office: Wales Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384408","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>No direct employees, agency staff or outsourced staff working for the Department for Transport and its Executive Agencies are paid less than the living wage.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-29T10:25:56.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384408/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384408/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-19","Department for Transport: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department and its subsidiary agencies are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384409","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Government is currently considering the Law Commission’s comprehensive report on reforming taxi and private hire vehicle legislation. In line with the protocol that exists between the Government and the Law Commission, we will provide a full response in due course.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T09:13:22.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384409/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384409/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-19","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish a response to the Law Commission report, Reforming the law on taxis and private hire services, Cm 8864, published in May 2014.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","3340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384410","Wales Office","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Wales Office has no direct employees or contracted workers. Staff at the Wales Office are subject to Ministry of Justice (MoJ) policies for pay purposes. No Wales Office staff, or agency staff working for the department, is paid less than the living wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-06-26T12:08:36.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384410/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384410/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-06-19","Wales Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many (a) direct employees, (b) agency staff and (c) outsourced staff working for his Department are paid less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384411","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-26","<p /> <p>The information as requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The Information for those in work is only available for Housing Benefit recipients whose claim is not passported: that is for those who do not receive Income Support, Jobseeker’s Allowance (Income-Based), Employment and Support Allowance (Income-Based), or Pension Credit (Guaranteed Credit). This information can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-26T14:06:14.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384411/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384411/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate he has made of the number of working households claiming housing benefit in (a) Lewisham, (b) London and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384412","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The information requested is not currently available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit (UC) in September 2013. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently quality assuring data for UC therefore it is not yet possible to give a definitive list of what statistics will be provided in the future. These statistics however will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The Departments release strategy and the latest official experimental statistics on UC can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T10:15:26.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384412/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384412/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many working recipients of universal credit have had their benefits reduced or stopped because a sanction was applied as a result of in-work conditionality.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384413","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The detailed information requested is not currently available. The Trusted Partner test was undertaken over an 8 week period with six landlords. We are evaluating the findings of this test as part of our on-going test and learn approach to working with key stakeholders in delivering Universal Credit. This evaluation will include recommendations on any next steps and future plans.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","3301","2015-06-24T10:33:30.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384413/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384413/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many landlords have trusted partner status for the purpose of placing tenants under alternative payment arrangements for universal credit; what proportion of universal credit recipients they cover; and what plans he has to extend that status.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384414","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>The detailed information requested is not currently available. The Trusted Partner test was undertaken over an 8 week period with six landlords. We are evaluating the findings of this test as part of our on-going test and learn approach to working with key stakeholders in delivering Universal Credit. This evaluation will include recommendations on any next steps and future plans.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","3300","2015-06-24T10:33:30.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384414/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384414/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of universal credit recipients have been placed under alternative payment arrangements by social landlords with trusted partner status.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384415","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p>The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit in September 2013. As outlined in the strategy, officials are quality assuring data for Universal Credit and formulating a definitive list of what statistics will be provided in the future. These statistics will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T10:28:30.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384415/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384415/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of universal credit recipients have been placed under alternative payment arrangements for the housing cost element of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384416","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The trial commenced on 20 April 2015 and therefore it is too early to make an assessment at this stage.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T10:22:06.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384416/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384416/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of in-work conditionality applied to recipients of universal credit who are in work.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384417","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>Last year saw an increase of 238,000 disabled people in work. The employment rate is now 46.3% - up 2.1% from last year. Our Disability Confident Campaign is ensuring that employers understand the benefits of employing disabled people. And our programmes, like Work Choice and Access to Work, are supporting disabled people into work. We will continue to build on this success.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T13:52:48.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384417/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384417/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to help people with disabilities back into work.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384418","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and Local Authorities regulate workplaces to assess compliance with health &amp; safety legislation. They also investigate complaints about working conditions, including excessive high (or low) temperatures. HSE targets its interventions on workplaces in higher risk sectors that include foundries and bakeries where high temperatures can be a concern. Inspectors can take enforcement action to improve conditions where they find problems.</p><p> </p><p>There is extensive guidance on the HSE website on this topic, including heat stress, and the practical steps that employers can take to manage risk. HSE is also simplifying this guidance to make it easier to use by small and medium sized enterprises. Guidance on various aspects of excessive high or low temperatures in the workplace can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/temperature/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/temperature/index.htm</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T14:21:20.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384418/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384418/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-19","Working Conditions: Temperature","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he has taken to ensure that employers comply with legislation and guidance on controlling excessively high temperatures in the workplace.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","3342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383708","Home Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>Face coverings can be worn in public places for a variety of legitimate reasons. In the context of a public order situation, where face coverings are being worn with the express intention of concealing identity, section 60AA of the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 enables a police officer in uniform to require any person to remove any item which the officer reasonably believes is being worn wholly or mainly for the purpose of concealing their identity. Section 60AA also enables a police officer in uniform to seize any item which they reasonably believe any person intends to use to conceal their identity.</p><p>A refusal to comply with a direction under this section of the Act is punishable by a fine of up to £1,000 and/or one month’s imprisonment.</p><p>These powers only apply in the locality and for the period for which an authorisation under section 60 or section 60AA of the Act has been given by a police officer of the rank of inspector or above. An inspector’s authorisation lasts for a maximum period of 24 hours, unless a police officer of the rank of superintendent or above authorises their use for a further 24 hours.</p><p>There are currently no plans to ban the use of masks in public order situations.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-24T13:48:49.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383708/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383708/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Demonstrations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to consider further the banning of the use of masks by demonstrators in order to avoid identification; and what assessment they have made of the current policy's impact on police forces and members of the community.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383709","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Government has made a commitment to bring forward legislation to ratify the Hague Convention and accede its two protocols at the first opportunity. Previous Governments were unable to find the necessary parliamentary time to do this earlier.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-02T15:46:01.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383709/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383709/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-18","UN Convention for Protection of Cultural Property in Event of Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they have not yet ratified the 1954 Hague Convention on the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict; and when they plan to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn",,"Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn","HL617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383710","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-02","<p>My Department will be conducting a public consultation later this year which will contain a number of proposals relating to the definition of Treasure and other measures set out in the Treasure Code of Practice. The Government's response to the consultation will be published thereafter.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-02T15:47:10.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383710/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383710/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-18","Treasure Act 1996","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to complete and publish the recommendations of their review of the Treasure Act 1996.","false","Biography information for Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn",,"Lord Renfrew of Kaimsthorn","HL618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383711","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Government is investing record amounts in building a world-class rail network across Great Britain, helping to create jobs, boost businesses, and secure long-term economic growth in every part of the country. We have asked the Peninsula Rail Task Force of local authorities and other key stakeholders in the South West to advise the Government of its strategic and local priorities for rail for the South-West of England for the period up until 2034. The report is expected by June 2016. The Campaign to Protect Rural England report is a useful contribution to the work of the Task Force.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-07-02T11:22:40.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383711/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383711/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Railways: Rural Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the evidence recently published in the Campaign to Protect Rural England report <i>Rural Reconnections: The social benefits of rail reopening</i>.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383712","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>The law states that it is illegal to assault a child. A parent or guardian hitting their child could be prosecuted for assault, but there is a defence of ‘reasonable chastisement’ that they may use in cases where they have given a child a mild smack. If physical chastisement results in injury to a child, including bruises, cuts or scratches, it can be charged as actual bodily harm or a more serious offence, for which the ‘reasonable chastisement’ defence cannot be used.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-07-02T16:28:22.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383712/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Corporal Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the judgment in <i>Re A </i>[2015] EWHC 1598 (Fam), in particular the judge's remarks that cultural context must be considered in such cases.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383713","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have responded to a Freedom of Information request for this information and the individual concerned has requested an internal review of our response. When this review is complete the individual will be informed of its outcome, including the reasons why any particular exemptions applied.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Thames Water Utilities Ltd (TWUL) is conducting this procurement under the Utilities Contracts Regulations 2006 which includes an obligation on the procuring authority to protect the confidentiality of bidders. Defra is also subject to a non-disclosure agreement with TWUL in relation to confidential information it has shared with Defra about this procurement. Revealing information on this procurement while it remains live other than as required by these Regulations would, or would be likely to, harm the commercial interests of both TWUL and the Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>TWUL will release appropriate details at the Preferred Bidder stage and Ofwat will consult on granting a project licence to the Preferred Bidder before Licence Award. In addition we will inform Parliament of the outcome of the procurement including relevant details once the procurement is complete. At this point the contract award notice will also be published in the Official Journal of the European Union.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-29T14:46:10.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383713/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383713/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Thames Tideway Tunnel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what basis they determined that providing information regarding the Thames Tideway Tunnel, including the number of tenders received, and the extent of the Government's Pre-Funded Risk Reserve, would prejudice the commercial interests of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and therefore fell under the exemption in section 43(2) of the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383714","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Freedom of Information Act provides an exception under Section 43 allowing commercially sensitive information to be withheld. Use of this exception is considered and applied as appropriate on a case-by-case basis.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-29T15:13:58.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383714/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383714/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what commercial interests the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs has that are exempt from the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383715","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>The events of June 1984 at Sri Harmandir Sahib in Amritsar led to a tragic loss of life and remain a source of deep pain to Sikhs everywhere around the world. We recognise the deep scars that this event left and the incredibly strong feelings that exist to this day. Relations between the Sikhs in India and the Indian government is an internal matter between those two parties.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-07-02T14:12:47.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383715/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383715/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Operation Blue Star","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Warsi on 7 April 2014 (HL WA244), and the oral answer by the Earl of Courtown on 16 June (HL Deb, col 1077), why they consider the mass killing of Sikhs in India to be a matter for the government of India alone, and not an issue for the international community.","false","Biography information for Lord Singh of Wimbledon",,"Lord Singh of Wimbledon","HL623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383716","Ministry of Justice","true","2015-07-02","<p><ins class="ministerial">The Coalition government legislated for secure colleges and we are now considering the next steps.</ins></p><br /><p><ins class="ministerial">Estimated s</ins><del class="ministerial">S</del>pend up to and including 30 April 2015 on the Secure College pathfinder was £1.56m resource (mainly expenditure on staff pay and procurement) and £4.04m capital (mainly design fees and site preparation costs).<ins class="ministerial"> These figures are subject to review by the National Audit Office in January 2016.</ins></p><br /><p>No additional costs would be incurred in the event that the pathfinder did not go ahead. The design work produced for the pathfinder could be used or adapted for various other forms of adult or youth custody. The prepared site at Glen Parva could be used for a range of developments.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-02T15:59:41.537Z","2015-12-07T16:13:38.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383716/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383716/answer",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383716/answer/previousversion/10857","Biography information for Lord Faulks","54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Secure Colleges: Leicestershire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the costs that will have been incurred in the event that the planned provision of a secure college on the Glen Parva site does not go ahead.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383717","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>We are committed to fulfilling our manifesto commitment in due course. Those who are still living are able to apply for a “disregard” under the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012.<br></p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T14:16:55.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383717/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383717/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Homosexuality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to be able to fulfil their manifesto pledge to introduce legislation to pardon those men, now deceased, who were historically convicted of gross indecency even though they would be innocent of any crime today; and whether this new law will extend the pardon to those men similarly convicted but still living.","false","Biography information for Lord Sharkey",,"Lord Sharkey","HL625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383718","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>Her Majesty's Government believes that the right approach is to consider the protection needs of individuals on an individual basis, and does not adopt a blanket approach to any one country.</p><p>Each asylum and human rights claim is considered on its individual merits in accordance with our international obligations and taking full account of conditions in the country concerned as they impact on the individual. Those found to be in need of international protection are provided with it. Those who have been found by the Home Office and the appeals process not to be in need of international protection and have no legal basis of stay in the UK are expected to return to their country of origin and may have their removal enforced.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-29T10:51:28.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383718/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383718/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Deportation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether their policy of returning migrants to their countries of origin excludes for humanitarian reasons certain countries of origin; and if so, which countries.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383719","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The United Kingdom has a proud tradition of providing protection to those who need it and we fulfil our responsibilities to all who claim asylum in the UK, irrespective of whether British military forces have previously been engaged in the country of origin.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-29T10:56:23.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383719/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383719/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the United Kingdom accepts a responsibility to grant asylum to refugees fleeing countries where in the last 10 years British military forces have been involved; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383720","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Scan Eagle Unmanned Aircraft System (UAS) offers enhanced maritime surveillance and is used to provide situational awareness to Royal Navy ships deployed to the Arabian Peninsula. In addition, a number of Reaper Remotely Piloted Aircraft Systems (RPAS) are currently operating in the Middle East in support of the Iraqi Government and International Coalition's ongoing operation to counter the threat of ISIL.</p><p> </p><p>Regardless of asset type or location, it is departmental policy not to confirm specific numbers of equipment platforms deployed on operations. Therefore, I am withholding the exact number of UAS/RPAS deployed on operations to safeguard operational security.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-06-25T15:36:42.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383720/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383720/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-18","Middle East: Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many British-controlled military unmanned aerial vehicles are currently operating within the Arabian Peninsula.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383721","Home Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>We are working with responsible social media companies to take robust action against terrorist material from groups like ISIL. Since 2010, over 90,000 pieces of terrorist-related material have been removed at the request of the dedicated Counter-Terrorism Internet Referral Unit. We want industry to go further and see them employ a zero tolerance approach to terrorist activity on their networks. We will continue encouraging companies to produce industry standards for the identification, removal and referral of terrorist activity. We have initiated work on this, together with the Minister for Internet Security at the Department for Culture Media and Sport.</p><p>We have also helped build the capacity of civil society groups through training and support, in order to give them the tools to challenge extremist messages online and provide credible alternatives. For example, the Home Secretary has given her personal support to the campaign launches of Families Matter, aimed at showing the distress caused to families by young people travelling to Syria and Iraq, and Making a Stand, promoting the voices of women to directly challenge the ISIL narrative.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-06-24T16:26:10.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383721/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383721/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Islamic State: Propaganda","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking directly to combat ISIL recruiting propaganda broadcast on social media.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383722","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-02","<p>In line with the Government’s devolution agenda, it is for local transport authorities to consider in the first instance whether the re-opening of a closed railway line is the best way to meet local transport needs and, if so, whether they would wish to prioritise any such re-opening in bidding for funding from the Government’s Local Growth Fund.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-07-02T11:23:09.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383722/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383722/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Railways: Rural Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which rural railway lines closed in the 1960s they would now favour reopening.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383723","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The UK is concerned about the shrinking space for civil society and freedom of expression in Azerbaijan, including the selective application of the rule of law. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has issued a number of statements expressing concern, most recently on 17 and 23 April 2015, following the sentencing of human rights defender, Rasul Jafarov, and human rights lawyer, Intigam Aliyev. We consistently raise our concerns both bilaterally and in international organisations such as the Council of Europe, the Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe and the UN. Our Ambassador in Baku raised concerns about freedom of the media in a statement on 17 June about the opening ceremony of the European Games in Baku.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-29T13:17:58.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383723/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383723/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Azerbaijan: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Azerbaijan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383724","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>We are concerned by the continuing detention of Ms Farghadani, apparently for drawing satirical cartoons and describing her ill-treatment in prison. Our non-resident Chargé d’affaires discussed freedom of expression in Iran when he met the Iranian Foreign Ministry’s Director General for Human Rights in May 2015. We have not raised the detention of Ms Farghadani specifically.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-24T15:53:45.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383724/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383724/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Iran","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Iran concerning the case of Atena Farghadani.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383725","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>We welcomed the early commitments by President Sirisena, and his new government, to make progress on human rights concerns in Sri Lanka. Since then there have been a number of positive steps taken, including the adoption of the 19th amendment to the constitution that restores the independence of key institutions; removal of restrictions on freedom of expression, with exiled journalists invited to return to the country and a number of banned websites unblocked; and, more democratic space with travel bans on foreign nationals visiting the North lifted and the Non-Governmental Organisations Secretariat moved from the Ministry of Defence to the Ministry of Policy Planning and Economic Affairs.</p><p>Challenges however remain, particularly over high military levels in the North and their involvement in civilian life and land occupation.</p><p> </p><p>The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights will make an assessment of progress at the September UN Human Rights Council.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-07-02T14:12:04.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383725/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383725/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Sri Lanka: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383726","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>We remain deeply concerned about the human rights situation in Eritrea. There are serious shortcomings in the rule of law, reports of arbitrary detention, and limits on freedom of speech. While we acknowledge some limited progress made by the Eritrean government, including ratifying the Convention Against Torture in 2014 and the hosting of a visit by international human rights experts in January 2015, we continue to call on Eritrea to take concrete steps to implement the recommendations of the 2014 Universal Periodic Review and to fulfil its international obligations.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear with the Eritrean government that the poor human rights situation is a driver of irregular migration, and the UK is committed to working with Eritrea on the issue. As with any country, decisions on migrant returns are made on a case-by-case basis in light of our international obligations and taking into account the latest available country information from a range of reliable sources. We only enforce removal when we and the courts conclude that it is safe to do so, with a safe route of return.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-25T14:51:04.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383726/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383726/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Eritrea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of human rights conditions in Eritrea; and how that assessment has influenced their policy on migrant returns to Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383727","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-01","<p>Since the London Girl Summit in 2014, the Government of Bangladesh has made progress on tackling the issue of child marriage. It is in the process of revising the Child Marriage Restraint Act to, for example, include tougher sanctions to improve enforcement. It is also in the process of finalising a 5 year National Plan of Action for Ending Child Marriage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Government continues to raise with the Government of Bangladesh our concerns regarding proposals to lower the legal age of marriage, including through Ministerial meetings and regular representations by the British High Commissioner and DFID officials.</p>",,"Baroness Verma","HL636 ; HL637","2015-07-01T16:00:11.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383727/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383727/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Bangladesh: Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the issue of child marriage was last raised with the government of Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383728","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-01","<p>Since the London Girl Summit in 2014, the Government of Bangladesh has made progress on tackling the issue of child marriage. It is in the process of revising the Child Marriage Restraint Act to, for example, include tougher sanctions to improve enforcement. It is also in the process of finalising a 5 year National Plan of Action for Ending Child Marriage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Government continues to raise with the Government of Bangladesh our concerns regarding proposals to lower the legal age of marriage, including through Ministerial meetings and regular representations by the British High Commissioner and DFID officials.</p>",,"Baroness Verma","HL635 ; HL637","2015-07-01T16:00:11.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383728/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383728/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Bangladesh: Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Bangladesh about its proposals to reduce the legal age of marriage for girls from 18 to 16.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383729","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-01","<p>Since the London Girl Summit in 2014, the Government of Bangladesh has made progress on tackling the issue of child marriage. It is in the process of revising the Child Marriage Restraint Act to, for example, include tougher sanctions to improve enforcement. It is also in the process of finalising a 5 year National Plan of Action for Ending Child Marriage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Government continues to raise with the Government of Bangladesh our concerns regarding proposals to lower the legal age of marriage, including through Ministerial meetings and regular representations by the British High Commissioner and DFID officials.</p>",,"Baroness Verma","HL635 ; HL636","2015-07-01T16:00:12.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383729/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383729/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Bangladesh: Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the progress made by the government of Bangladesh in implementing the commitments on child marriage it made at the London Girl Summit in 2014.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383730","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-02","<p>Since the Girl Summit in London in 2014, the Department for International Development has focused on delivering the UK Government’s commitment to ending FGM and Child, Early and Forced Marriage through its flagship £35 million FGM programme and recently launched £36 million programme to accelerate action to end Child marriage. DFID will co-host an event with the Canadian High Commission to mark the first anniversary of the Girl Summit and will produce, together with UNICEF a stocktake of global progress over the past year in working to end FGM and Child, Early and Forced marriage.</p><p> </p><p>Progress on our domestic commitments includes a range of measures to significantly strengthen the law on FGM through the Serious Crime Act, a further £1.6 million for the next stage of the Department of Health’s FGM prevention programme, and a programme of outreach by the Government’s FGM Unit.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-07-02T16:27:48.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383730/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Females: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans, if any, are in place to mark the one-year anniversary of the London Girl Summit.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383731","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>We regularly raise human rights concerns with the government of Cambodia and encouraged them to carry out a full consultation before publishing the draft law on non-governmental organisations. EU Ambassadors have also made their views known to the Cambodian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of the Interior, and our Ambassador in Phnom Penh called on the Council of Ministers’ Spokesman, who is tasked with managing the law’s passage. On 5 June, a joint letter from member states of the Community of Democracies Working Group on Enabling and Protecting Civil Society, and the Stand with Civil Society initiative, was handed to the Cambodian government. The letter called for a meaningful public consultation and urged the Cambodian government to ensure the legislation does not constrain basic freedoms of speech, association and peaceful assembly, in line with Cambodia’s international obligations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-29T13:20:04.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383731/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383731/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-18","Cambodia: Freedom of Association","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Cambodia regarding the draft law on non-governmental organisations currently before the Cambodian Parliament, which restricts freedom of association.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383732","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Ministry of Defence, in collaboration with The Royal British Legion, will lead national commemorations in central London on Saturday 15 August 2015 to mark the 70th Anniversary of Victory over Japan Day (VJ Day 70).</p><p> </p><p>The event will begin with a special commemoration on Horse Guards Parade, attended by senior political and military representatives, veterans and their families, which will include at its heart a traditional Drumhead Service. Current members of the Armed Forces will then lead veterans and their families in a parade down Whitehall, past the Cenotaph and the statue of Field Marshal Lord Slim, who famously led the 14th Army.</p><p> </p><p>Further details of the VJ Day 70 programme will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Invitations to participate in VJ Day 70 have been issued to representatives from all declared allies of the UK, Commonwealth countries, overseas territories and Crown Dependencies. In this way, the contribution and sacrifices made during the Far East campaign by communities such as the Burmese hill tribes will be recognised on this milestone anniversary.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-06-30T15:21:06.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383732/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383732/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-18","VJ Day","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what commemorative events they have planned for the 70th anniversary of Victory over Japan Day.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383733","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-02","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Bacteria naturally adapt and find new ways to survive the effects of an antibiotic; any use of an antibiotic accelerates the risk that bacteria will develop resistance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to carry out research and surveillance to better understand the link between antibiotic use and development of resistance.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-07-02T13:30:07.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383733/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383733/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Livestock: Antibiotics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the use of antibiotic products on farm animals contributes significantly to the antibiotic resistance problem.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383734","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) leads on energy policy including hydraulic fracturing for shale gas and oil. Defra is responsible for the environmental aspects of shale gas and oil policy, with the exception of climate change and seismicity issues which are a DECC lead.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra’s responsibility extends to England only as environmental policy is a devolved matter. The Environment Agency is the environmental regulator in England which is responsible for issuing environmental permits to ensure that operations are undertaken in a way which protects people and the environment.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-29T15:15:20.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383734/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383734/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Fracking: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how responsibility for the regulation of fracking is divided between the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and the Department of Energy and Climate Change.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383735","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Flood defences are a priority for this Government. We are spending £2.3 billion on more than 1,500 schemes to improve defences through a six-year programme of work up to 2021. This is projected to reduce overall flood risk by 5%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-24T11:18:51.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383735/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383735/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Flood Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to invest in flood defences.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383736","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>Our immediate priority, over the next year, is to simplify the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) Reducing the administrative burden of the CAP on farmers is a necessary part of increasing the competitiveness of our food and farming sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have pushed hard in the EU for reforms such as a review of the greening rules which place unnecessary burdens on farmers for limited environmental benefits. There is an opportunity to deliver some reforms to the CAP as part of the Commission’s CAP simplification programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-30T16:33:54.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383736/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383736/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Common Agricultural Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to seek reforms to the Common Agricultural Policy in order to boost productivity and sustainability.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383737","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-01","<p>The Government has allocated £16.66 million to the Lincolnshire broadband project. 79,824 homes and businesses had been given access superfast broadband by 31 March 2015 as a result of the project.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-01T16:23:23.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383737/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383737/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-18","Broadband: Lincolnshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to invest in high-speed broadband in Lincolnshire.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383738","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-01","<p>The British fruit industry forms a vital part of our food production. We are working with industry to develop a long-term plan to buy more, sell more and grow more British food and ensure our industry can become a world leader.</p><p> </p><p>There has been a steady increase in the total value of UK fruit production over the past five years. Developments in new varieties, production techniques and storage have contributed to increased productivity. More UK-grown fruits are available to British consumers than ever before.</p><p> </p><p>This Government has taken a lead in buying more British food, implementing the Bonfield plan for public sector procurement. It is opening a potential £400 million of new business by making it easier for schools, hospitals and canteens to buy high-quality local food, including British-grown fruit.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Government’s Agri-Tech Strategy we have announced £5.3 million of government and industry funding for seven projects to address challenges for the British fruit sector. These projects will tackle diseases and other issues that limit the supply of British produce.</p><p> </p><p>The industry and government are working to promote the long-term health benefits of eating fruit and vegetables. The UK school fruit and vegetable scheme ensures that every child under the age of seven in school receives a piece of fruit or vegetable every day to help build healthy eating habits.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-07-01T15:55:44.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383738/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383738/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Fruit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that more British-grown fruit is sold within the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383739","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The information requested is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Number of 3- and 4-year-olds benefitting from funded early education places in January each year</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong> </strong></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Nursery schools</strong></p></td><td><p>37,520</p></td><td><p>38,730</p></td><td><p>39,300</p></td><td><p>38,640</p></td><td><p>37,590</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Nursery classes in primary schools</strong></p></td><td><p>291,510</p></td><td><p>296,550</p></td><td><p>302,720</p></td><td><p>297,090</p></td><td><p>296,840</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Early Years Census (EYC), School Census (SC), and School Level Annual School Census (SLASC)</p><p> </p><p>The information is published as part of the statistical first release entitled “Provision for children under 5 years of age”.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has also estimated that in 2013 there were 230,000 more registered childcare and early education places than in 2009, based on data from the Childcare and Early Years Providers Survey. The basis for this internal estimate differs significantly from the above because: registered childcare includes unfunded childcare places; covering places for all children aged 0-5; including places in private and voluntary providers and provided by childminders. The estimate excludes out of school settings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-25T15:35:40.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383739/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383739/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many three and four year-old children benefitted from the 15 hours free childcare allowance in (1) nursery classes in primary schools, and (2) maintained nursery schools, in each of the previous five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383740","Department for Education","false","2015-07-01","<p>Primary schools are an important provider of places for the current funded entitlement of 15 hours, with almost 297,000 three and four-year-olds benefiting from funded early education places in primary schools in January 2014. This is 94% all of three-year-olds and 99% of all four-year-olds. Schools have a track record of creating capacity by re-arranging their existing nursery provision, as we have seen where they have expanded their nurseries or worked in partnership with other providers, including for the delivery of funded two-year-old places.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The decision whether or not to make these sorts of changes is a choice for schools to make, but we would encourage them to consider establishing or expanding nursery provision, either directly by the school or in partnership with a third party. We will be working closely with schools and other providers to understand more about their capacity and what approaches might work best in their setting.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-07-01T16:22:14.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383740/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383740/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of how many primary schools have spare capacity to accommodate three and four year-old children of parents entitled to the new 30 hours free childcare allowance.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383741","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>The government welcomes the work of the House of Lords Affordable Childcare Select Committee and the excellent report it produced.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a new government, we want to consider the report in full as we develop our own childcare proposals. The government will respond to the Committee’s report in the autumn.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-30T15:19:21.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383741/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383741/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Affordable Childcare Select Committee (HL)","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to respond to the report of the Select Committee on Affordable Childcare.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383742","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>All nursery provision, including that provided by Free Schools, is subject to the requirements set out in the statutory Framework for the Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Nursery provision that is part of a Free School must meet the needs of all children and ensure their safety. The staff qualification requirements and adult to child ratios for all providers are set out in paragraphs 3.28 to 3.39 of the EYFS Framework which is attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Providing other staff hold the necessary qualifications as set out in the EYFS, Free Schools (as can all early years providers) may employ unqualified staff as part of their staffing mix.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-25T10:59:18.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383742/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383742/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Nurseries: Free Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether nurseries linked to free schools will be allowed to employ unqualified staff.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383743","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>On 25 June 2015, the government made a policy statement available to the House of Lords, setting out further details on the government’s intention behind the Childcare Bill, to aid Peers in their scrutiny of the Bill ahead of Committee Stage.</p><p> </p><p>The government wants to engage with parents, providers and employers about how they currently access and deliver childcare and what they think are the relative priorities for an additional 15 hours of childcare. This will begin in the summer.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear what is important to parents in choosing a childcare provider and their views on how the extended entitlement will best meet their childcare needs. We will make the best use of the consultation channels available, including social media and online forums and we are keen to work with employers who have a shared interest in this agenda to hear the views of their busy, working parents. Many voluntary and community sector organisations have already offered to host events for parents and providers, including groups representing and supporting disabled children and their parents, and we will be working with them to plan these events. We are also hoping to work closer with employer organisations such as the Confederation of British Industry who have welcomed the extension of the free childcare entitlement.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL652","2015-06-30T15:38:43.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383743/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383743/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which disabled children's groups they plan to consult on the impact of the Childcare Bill [HL].","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383744","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>On 25 June 2015, the government made a policy statement available to the House of Lords, setting out further details on the government’s intention behind the Childcare Bill, to aid Peers in their scrutiny of the Bill ahead of Committee Stage.</p><p> </p><p>The government wants to engage with parents, providers and employers about how they currently access and deliver childcare and what they think are the relative priorities for an additional 15 hours of childcare. This will begin in the summer.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear what is important to parents in choosing a childcare provider and their views on how the extended entitlement will best meet their childcare needs. We will make the best use of the consultation channels available, including social media and online forums and we are keen to work with employers who have a shared interest in this agenda to hear the views of their busy, working parents. Many voluntary and community sector organisations have already offered to host events for parents and providers, including groups representing and supporting disabled children and their parents, and we will be working with them to plan these events. We are also hoping to work closer with employer organisations such as the Confederation of British Industry who have welcomed the extension of the free childcare entitlement.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL651","2015-06-30T15:38:43.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383744/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383744/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which maintained sector providers they plan to consult on the impact of the Childcare Bill [HL].","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383745","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>The government has made clear its intention to roll out the extended free childcare entitlement in certain areas from September 2016 in advance of implementation from 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The government is currently considering where early implementation of the extended entitlement should take place, including the number of areas and the locations to ensure geographic balance. The areas will test out the important operational details for delivering the extended entitlement and provide a source of intelligence to support the government in refining the systems to deliver the entitlement. We will announce further details in the autumn.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-30T15:36:30.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383745/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383745/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who will be asked to review the conclusions of the pilot schemes for the measures to be implemented under the Childcare Bill [HL] in 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383746","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>Clause 1(5) (k) of the Childcare Bill enables regulations to make provision for criminal offences in connection with the provision of information and documents and disclosure of information for the purposes of eligibility checking, mentioned in paragraphs (5) (i) and (j) of the Bill only.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in the policy statement made available to the House of Lords on 25 June 2015, the government’s intention is that any new offences should align with existing offences for schemes involving information sharing and self-declaration. Clause 1(7) provides for a cap on the penalty that may be imposed on indictment, namely a maximum term of imprisonment of two years, with or without a fine. This is an appropriate safeguard, which might be appropriate in large scale fraud cases, or misuse of sensitive personal tax data, whilst retaining the option of imposing lesser penalties.</p><p> </p><p>It would be for the police and the relevant prosecuting authority to decide whether to bring a prosecution and at what level.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-30T15:32:29.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383746/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383746/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to publish details of possible new criminal offences to support regulations made under the Childcare Bill [HL].","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383747","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>I very much welcome publication of the Lambeth Declaration 2015 on climate change and would like to thank the Bishop of Salisbury, Nick Holtam, for his work in securing it.</p><p>Faith communities have a strong track record of bringing about real and lasting change at every level of society so we welcome this significant intervention on climate change and urge all faiths to work together in the lead up to Paris Climate Summit and beyond.</p><p>We all have a responsibility to learn how to live and develop sustainably in a world of finite resources. Caring for our environment and being conscious of our impact on it is central to many faith’s beliefs and something that faith groups communicate better than anyone.</p><p>The UK Government is working hard to secure a global climate deal in Paris and will continue to work with stakeholders from all sectors to help deliver an ambitious international agreement on climate change.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-06-23T14:34:24.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383747/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383747/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the Lambeth Declaration on Climate Change, signed by the leaders of the United Kingdom’s Christian and other faith communities and launched on 17 June.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Salisbury",,"The Lord Bishop of Salisbury","HL655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383748","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Prime Minister, with other G7 leaders, recently reaffirmed their commitment to jointly mobilise USD $100 billion of climate finance a year by 2020 from a wide variety of sources, both public and private, and that they stand ready to engage proactively in the negotiations of the finance provisions of the Paris outcome. The UK has a strong track record on climate finance and is meeting its commitments, for example committing £3.87bn through the International Climate Fund (ICF) in this spending review period. Climate finance commitments beyond 2015/16 will be determined through the forthcoming Spending Review process.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-06-30T11:23:47.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383748/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383748/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to address the issue of climate finance at the forthcoming United Nations Climate Change conference in Paris; and whether they plan to commit the United Kingdom to budgeting for climate finance arrangements up to 2020.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Salisbury",,"The Lord Bishop of Salisbury","HL656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383749","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-24","<p>Seven applications were submitted from Northern Ireland for the first three tranches of the fund.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-06-24T15:33:22.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383749/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383749/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-18","Armed Forces Covenant: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many applications were submitted from Northern Ireland for the first three tranches of the Armed Forces Covenant (Libor) Fund.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383750","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-02","<p>Sheffield City Council and officers at South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive carried out an assessment of the relative economic impacts of siting the South Yorkshire HS2 station in Sheffield City Centre or at Meadowhall. The conclusions of this assessment were set out by HS2 Ltd in their report <em>Options for phase two of the high speed rail network </em>(March 2012).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-07-02T11:23:55.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383750/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 18 June (HL453), whether any cost-benefit analysis has been conducted purely on the impact on the economic performance of South Yorkshire of siting the HS2 station at Sheffield City Centre and Meadowhall, rather than on a demand and appraisal basis; and if such analysis has been conducted, when the results will be published.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383751","Attorney General","false","2015-06-25","<p>The information requested in respect of the Attorney General’s Office, HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate and the Government Legal Department (formally TSol) remains unchanged from that given in the former Solicitor General’s answer to question 183631 on 22 January 2014 (Official Report, Col 192W). Information relating to the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) and the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is detailed below.</p><p>The SFO is a tenant in 2-4 Cockspur Street, London, SW1Y 5BS which is owned by the Crown Estate. The Canadian High Commission (CHC) has taken out a 101 year lease from the Crown Estate for the building and the SFO makes rental payments to the CHC for the space it occupies. The rent paid by the SFO for 2014-15 financial year amounted to £1,733,619 (including non-recoverable VAT).</p><p>In March 2015 the SFO rented additional temporary office space as part of one of its blockbuster investigations. Following discussions with the Government Property Unit (GPU) a short term lease for temporary accommodation was agreed with Regus Management. This lease is due to run from 16 March to 30 June 2015 and rental payments for the 2014-15 financial year amounted to £15,690 (including non-recoverable VAT).</p><p>According to records held by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) property managing agent (DTZ), the CPS leases the following buildings that are owned or part-owned privately. The rent figures exclude VAT.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><thead><tr><td><p><strong>Property</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Town</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Landlord</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Rent £p/a</strong></p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Emlyn Hughes House</p></td><td><p>Barrow-in-Furness</p></td><td><p>Barrow-in-furness Borough</p><p>Council</p></td><td><p>33,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Colmore Gate</p></td><td><p>Birmingham</p></td><td><p>CIP Property (AIPT) Ltd</p