"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383832","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Cities and Local Government Devolution Bill is an enabling measure providing for the transfer of existing powers from one public body to another through secondary legislation.<br><br>The powers to be devolved in each case will be those agreed in each Deal.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-23T11:49:37.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383832/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383832/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-18","Cities and Local Government Devolution Bill (HL)","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what functions he plans to delegate to a combined authority should Clause 6 of the Cities and Local Government Devolution Bill pass into law.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383833","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>Sponsored academies have played a significant role over several years in bringing about the improvement of many failing and struggling schools in some of our most disadvantaged areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>By 2014, the proportion of pupils that achieved five good GCSEs, including English and Mathematics, in sponsored secondary academies open for four years had risen by an average of 6.4 percentage points compared to the schools that they replaced (a rise from 36.8 per cent in 2010 to 43.2 per cent in 2014). Over the same period, results in local authority schools rose by an average of 1.3 percentage points (a rise from 54.4 per cent to 55.7 per cent).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The first sponsored primary academies had been open for two years by the time of the 2014 results. The proportion of pupils that achieved the expected level in reading, writing and mathematics increased by an average of 9 percentage points (from 58 per cent to 67 per cent) in that time, compared to an average 4 percentage point rise (from 75 per cent to 79 per cent) in local authority schools.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We want more schools to achieve these rates of improvement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Statistics for the attainment of local authority schools and academies can be found on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-education/about/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-education/about/statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, many successful schools have become converter academies and are sharing their educational expertise with other schools. Over half of approved sponsors are converter academies. In 2014, attainment in converter academies continued to remain above that in local authority schools.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-25T08:56:09.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383833/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383833/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what evidence her Department holds to support the proposition that academies are better performers than local authority schools; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","3142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383834","Department for Education","false","2015-06-23","<p>We want all pupils to study rigorous academic subjects which give them the best start in life and help to keep their options open. We acknowledge that the EBacc will be inappropriate for a small minority of pupils, and we will work with the sector to identify them and consider what is expected for them. We plan to consult on detailed proposals in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-23T14:39:33.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383834/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383834/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the expectation that all students should take Ebacc subjects applies to university technical college and studio school students.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383835","Department for Education","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Department does not collect information on the number of anticipated closures but expects local authorities to update the Sure Start On database when a children's centre is closed. Local authorities have duties under the Childcare Act 2006 to ensure sufficient children’s centres to meet local need and to ensure they consult before any significant changes are made, including taking into account the views of local families and communities. It is for local authorities, taking into account this consultation with their local communities, to determine the most effective way of delivering children’s centre services to meet local need. There remains a presumption against closure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below sets out the number of children’s centres that have closed and opened in each year from 2010 to 2014 according to information supplied by local authorities to the Sure Start On database. These represent the latest published figures. Data on the changes to children’s centre numbers for 2015 to date will be available in early July.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of centres</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Opened</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Closed</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>83</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","3205","2015-06-26T07:49:38.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383835/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383835/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of children's centres which have (a) closed and (b) opened in each year from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383836","Department for Education","false","2015-06-23","<p>As the Minister in the Department for Education with specific responsibility for children and young people’s mental health issues I have recently met my counterpart in Department of Health (DH), Alastair Burt.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have confirmed that our departments will continue to work closely together on reforms to children and young people’s mental health services following the publication in March of ‘Future in Mind’, the report of the work of the DH and NHS England task force on children and young people’s mental health and well-being. Joined up action across health, education and children’s services will help to make sure that understanding of mental health is on an equal footing with physical health, that mental health issues are not stigmatising for children and young people, and that services are accessible where support is needed and responsive to the needs of individuals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education is already committing £1.5m to the development of a joint training pilot with NHS England to train mental health leads in schools and specialist child and adolescent mental health services. In addition the department is providing funding worth £4.7m this year to support 17 projects delivering a wide range of support across the country to children and young people with mental health issues. The department has also funded PSHE Association guidance on teaching about mental health in PSHE which was published in March 2015. This will be followed by a set of lesson plans spanning key stages 1-4 which will be available for schools before the end of the summer term.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-23T14:13:28.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383836/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383836/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Health about child and adolescent mental health services in England; and what the conclusion was of those discussions.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383837","Department for Education","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Department does not collect information on the number of anticipated closures but expects local authorities to update the Sure Start On database when a children's centre is closed. Local authorities have duties under the Childcare Act 2006 to ensure sufficient children’s centres to meet local need and to ensure they consult before any significant changes are made, including taking into account the views of local families and communities. It is for local authorities, taking into account this consultation with their local communities, to determine the most effective way of delivering children’s centre services to meet local need. There remains a presumption against closure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below sets out the number of children’s centres that have closed and opened in each year from 2010 to 2014 according to information supplied by local authorities to the Sure Start On database. These represent the latest published figures. Data on the changes to children’s centre numbers for 2015 to date will be available in early July.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of centres</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Opened</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Closed</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>83</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","3237","2015-06-26T07:49:37.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383837/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383837/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Children's Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of children's centres which will close in England and Wales between 2015 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383838","Home Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. Police forces provide routine statistics on notifiable offences to the Home Office. However, these cannot be split as requested. They do not specify the victim’s accommodation or whether they were under 18.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-25T15:50:55.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383838/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383838/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Supported Housing: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many crimes were committed against people aged under 18 in supported accommodation in each region and constituent part of the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","3216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383839","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Secretary of State unfortunately is unable to meet with the Skills Funding Agency (SFA) at this time. Other Ministers and officials frequently meet with the SFA to discuss matters as they arise.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T09:05:29.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383839/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383839/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will meet the Skills Funding Agency to discuss the number of places her Department will fund in the coming year.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383840","Department for Education","false","2015-06-24","<p>A value for money assessment is made prior to a school being approved into pre-opening and again before a capital budget is approved. This includes an assessment of whether temporary accommodation is needed. The cost of temporary accommodation varies depending on the type of accommodation used.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-24T09:48:03.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383840/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383840/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Free Schools: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the average cost of establishing a free school in temporary accommodation before moving that school to another building; and whether costs of such temporary accommodation and moves are included by her Department in value for money assessments.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383841","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The allocations for the education of 16 to 19-year-olds in 2015/16 were announced by the end of March. The allocations remain in place and we are not planning to change them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State’s policy officials frequently meet with the Education Funding Agency to discuss matters as they arise.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-25T13:19:15.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383841/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383841/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will meet the Education Funding Agency to discuss the number of course places her Department will fund in the coming year.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383842","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>I would be happy to meet the Honorable Member for Dudley North and representatives of Dudley College to discuss funding allocations following the Spending Review. The EFA have confirmed that allocations for 16 to19-year-olds made in March 2015 for the 2015 to 2016 academic year are secure.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T09:03:32.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383842/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383842/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will meet representatives of Dudley College to discuss upcoming funding allocations for (a) adult skills, (b) the Skills Funding Agency and (c) the Education Funding Agency.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","3230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383843","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The department does not collect information on the percentage of children of any faith or of no faith in free schools. Of the 212 open mainstream free schools there are 8 single-sex schools (3.8%), of which 6 (75%) have a religious character.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","3208 ; 3209","2015-06-25T13:13:59.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383843/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383843/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Free Schools: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools of a religious character have (a) 50 to 100 per cent (b) 40 to 49 per cent, (c) 30 to 39 per cent, (d) 20 to 29 per cent, (e) 10 to 19, (f) less than 10 per cent, (g) less than five per cent and (h) less than one per cent of children from other faiths or no faith.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383844","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The department does not collect information on the percentage of children of any faith or of no faith in free schools. Of the 212 open mainstream free schools there are 8 single-sex schools (3.8%), of which 6 (75%) have a religious character.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","3207 ; 3209","2015-06-25T13:13:59.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383844/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383844/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Free Schools: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of free schools is single-sex.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383845","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The department does not collect information on the percentage of children of any faith or of no faith in free schools. Of the 212 open mainstream free schools there are 8 single-sex schools (3.8%), of which 6 (75%) have a religious character.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","3207 ; 3208","2015-06-25T13:13:59.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383845/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Free Schools: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of single-sex free schools is of a religious character.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383846","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>Since May 2010 the department has reduced the size of its estate from 30 properties, at a cost of circa £51m per annum, to six properties costing circa £31m per annum. As part of its estates strategy in 2012 the department announced an ambitious programme to reduce its estate from twelve sites to six, while maximising the efficiency of the buildings retained. This has now been achieved by reducing the amount of space we use, by surrendering unwanted facilities to landlords and through sub-letting vacant space to other organisations.</p><p> </p><p>The Department also plans to vacate Sanctuary Buildings at lease expiry in 2017 and relocate to a Government owned freehold building, which will generate a further saving of c£8.5m per year.</p><p> </p><p>The department currently occupies ten properties which are owned or part-owned privately. These are listed in the following table:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Property</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Landlord</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Gross Rent (£) Per Annum (exc VAT)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Net Rent (£) Per Annum (exc VAT)(3)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bishopsgate House, Darlington</p></td><td><p>Darlington Borough Council</p></td><td><p>432,420.00</p></td><td><p>419,447.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Earlsdon Park, Coventry</p></td><td><p>MCD (Coventry) Ltd (acting by J Pitt &amp; B Moon)</p></td><td><p>1,211,301.00</p></td><td><p>1,211,301.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National College, Nottingham</p></td><td><p>University of Nottingham</p></td><td><p>Peppercorn(1)</p></td><td><p>Peppercorn(1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Piccadilly Gate, Manchester</p></td><td><p>London and Continental Railways Limited</p></td><td><p>1,009,255.45</p></td><td><p>736,261.02</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sanctuary Buildings, London</p></td><td><p>Blackstone Property Management Ltd</p></td><td><p>10,300,000.00</p></td><td><p>7,854,780.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>St Pauls, Sheffield</p></td><td><p>St Pauls Place Management Ltd</p></td><td><p>Peppercorn(1)</p></td><td><p>Peppercorn(1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Trafalgar House, Croydon(2)</p></td><td><p>Land Registry</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>High Trees, Hemel Hempstead(2)</p></td><td><p>Department for Communities and Local Government</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rivergate, Bristol(2)</p></td><td><p>Department for Communities and Local Government</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Eastbrook House, Cambridge(2)</p></td><td><p>Department for Communities and Local Government</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>1 A peppercorn rent represents a nominal consideration to satisfy the legal requirements for creation of a contract.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>2 The department are minor occupiers under a Memorandum of Terms of Occupancy (MOTO).</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>3 Net Rent includes all receipts from tenants in the buildings.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-25T13:07:38.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383846/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383846/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Department for Education: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which buildings occupied by her Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383847","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The government is satisfied that free schools continue to offer good value for money: one in four of the free schools inspected by Ofsted have been judged outstanding compared to one in five of all other schools. We are working towards at least 500 new free schools by the end of this parliament.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-25T13:17:36.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383847/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383847/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 4 March 2014 to Question 189394, what comparative assessment she has made of the value for money of (a) community schools other than academies and (b) free schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383848","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The department has no plans to publish the information requested.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-25T13:11:52.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383848/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383848/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 12 February 2014 to Question 187197, on school admissions, if she will place in the Library copies of (a) all those letters to local authorities where a free school is being proposed and (b) any representations from local authorities in response to those letters.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","3064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383849","Department for Education","false","2015-06-23","<p>Most of this information is already available in the one place. Since 2011, as part of the government’s transparency agenda, the performance website expanded greatly. The location of each school and its unique reference number are shown on each school’s entry on the School Performance Tables website. This page also provides PDF versions of academy funding agreements, annual reports and financial statements which contain the name of the company with whom the Secretary of State has a funding agreement and its Companies House registration number. The Ofsted inspection reports website provides a direct link to each school’s performance tables entry under ‘further links’.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly review the content and functionality of our website and will consider whether it would be helpful to add each school’s local authority establishment number to the website.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-23T16:11:42.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383849/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383849/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish in one place on gov.uk where each school is located, each school's unique reference number and local authority establishment number, the URL for each such school's page on her Department's school and college performance tables website, the URL for each such page on Ofsted's Inspection Report website, the name of the company which has an academy funding agreement, and the Companies House registration number of each of those companies.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3077"
