.parliament.uk/resources/383850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383850/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-18","Department for Education: Ministers' Private Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time equivalent staff at each civil service grade are employed in the private office of each Minister in her Department.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","3131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383851","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-24","<p>“Driving Investment: a plan to reform the Oil and Gas Fiscal regime”, published at Autumn Statement 2014, set out a long-term plan for the future of the oil and gas fiscal regime to ensure the North Sea continues to attract investment and safeguard the future of this vital national asset.</p><p> </p><p>Delivering on this, the Chancellor announced a radical package of reforms in March, including an immediate cut to the rate of the Supplementary Charge, from 30% to 20%, which is already in effect; a reduction to Petroleum Revenue Tax, from 50% to 35%, from January 2016; and the introduction of a new Investment Allowance to support investment in the UK Continental Shelf. The government also provided £20m of funding for a programme of seismic surveying in 2015-16 to boost exploration in under-explored areas of the basin.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This package is worth £1.3bn over the next 5 years and is expected to deliver at least £4bn of additional investment and increase production by 15% by 2019, the equivalent of 0.1% of GDP.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-06-24T16:09:02.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383851/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383851/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-18","Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will offer financial incentives to the UK oil and gas sector to stimulate growth.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","3122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383852","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Papal Encyclical raises a number of important issues, including the protection of the planet</p><p>The UK Government recognises the importance of tackling climate change. We were the first country to put in place a legally binding long-term target, and we have established five year carbon budgets for reducing emissions into the late 2020s. We met our first carbon budget last year, and according to our latest projections we are on track to meet the next two carbon budgets. The UK Government is also working hard to secure a global climate deal in Paris later this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T16:01:44.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383852/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383852/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policies on climate change of the Papal encyclical issued on 18 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","3120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383853","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Renewables Obligation Closure Order 2014 no. 2388 implements some of the policies set out in the March 2014 Government response to the consultation on transition from the Renewables Obligation (RO) to contracts for difference (CfDs), and associated grace periods [1]. It provides for the closure of the RO to new generating capacity in Great Britain (with grace periods) after 31 March 2017, at which point CfDs will become the main support mechanism for large–scale low-carbon electricity generation. The order was amended by the Renewables Obligation Closure (Amendment) Order 2015 No. 920 which provides for the closure of the RO to solar projects above 5MW in Great Britain (with grace periods) after 31 March 2015.</p><p>On 18<sup>th</sup> June, my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced plans to close the RO to new onshore wind projects in Great Britain from 31 March 2016, with a proposed grace period. This will be done through the Energy Bill, meaning that any changes will be subject to full Parliamentary scrutiny.</p><p><em>1</em><em>]</em><em> ‘ Government Response to the consultation on the Renewables Obligation transition and on grace periods’ (March 2014) at : <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/289076/Transition_and_Grace_Periods_Government_Response_-_12_Mar_2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/289076/Transition_and_Grace_Periods_Government_Response_-_12_Mar_2014.pdf</a>.</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T16:06:06.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383853/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383853/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her policy is on the continuation of operation of the Renewables Obligation Closure Order 2014, no 2388, before the introduction of primary legislation to close the Renewables Obligation to new onshore wind from 1 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","3082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383854","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change (DECC) currently occupies, wholly or partly, four buildings in London and one in Aberdeen. These buildings form the Core Estate of the Department and are currently required in order for DECC to carry out its business.</p><p>In London, DECC fully occupies ‘3 Whitehall Place’ and ‘55 Whitehall’, whilst partly occupying space at ‘Kings Buildings’ (3.5 floors of 9 floor building) and ‘One Victoria St’ (approx. 500SqM).</p><ul><li>3 Whitehall Place – DECC pay rent to the Department for the Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs (DEFRA) who lease from a private landlord.</li><li>55 Whitehall – DECC pay rent to the Crown Estate (landlord).</li><li>Kings Buildings – DECC pay rent to Transport for London (TFL) who lease from a private landlord.</li><li>One Victoria St – DECC pay rent to the Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills (BIS) who lease from a private landlord.</li></ul><p>In Aberdeen, DECC partly occupies space at Atholl House’ (2 floors of a 7 floor building) – DECC pay rent to BIS who lease from a private landlord.</p><p>In all cases above, the Department cannot release the value of these rental payments as this is considered commercially sensitive information.</p><p>As part of the Government’s Strategic Land &amp; Property Review (SLPR), all Departments are working to reduce property costs either by exiting leasehold agreements or by selling/sub-letting freeholds. As part of this, DECC plan to amalgamate all of its London staff in 3 Whitehall Place and 55 Whitehall during this financial year, thereby exiting Kings Buildings and One Victoria St. This will be achieved by creating a ‘smarter’, more flexible way of working.</p><p>The Government Property Unit (GPU) has created a portal - Find Me Some Government Space (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property</a>) - for more efficient marketing of surplus land and buildings. This is searchable by developers, community groups and the general public.</p><p>Further information on the the efficiency and sustainability of property in the government's civil estate is published in our State of the Estate Report 2013 - 2014 available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-07T12:59:14.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383854/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383854/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which buildings occupied by her Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383855","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have extensive contacts with onshore wind developers and have, in recent weeks, received a range of information on investments in projects in the onshore wind pipeline. We will continue to engage with developers, investors and stakeholders as we implement the onshore wind manifesto commitment. We will consider carefully the level of investment that developers are likely to bring forward under the proposals announced by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 18 June.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T16:07:19.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383855/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383855/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what discussions she Department has had with investors who have sunk costs in the onshore wind pipeline under the Renewables Obligation.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","3092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383856","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have proposed that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our propose closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3218 ; 3219 ; 3220","2015-06-29T16:08:57.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383856/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383856/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power: Lincolnshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Written Statement of 18 June 2015, HC WS40, whether her Department plans to offer support under the Renewables Obligation to the proposed Temple Hill wind farm.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","3217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383857","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have proposed that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our propose closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3217 ; 3219 ; 3220","2015-06-29T16:08:57.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383857/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383857/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power: Lincolnshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Written Statement of 18 June 2015, HC WS40, whether her Department plans to offer support under the Renewables Obligation to the proposed Fulbeck Airfield wind farm.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","3218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383858","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have proposed that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our propose closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3217 ; 3218 ; 3220","2015-06-29T16:08:58.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383858/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383858/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power: Lincolnshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Written Statement of 18 June 2015, HC WS40, whether her Department plans to offer support under the Renewables Obligation to the proposed Nocton Fen wind farm.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","3219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383859","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>We have proposed that onshore wind projects wishing to access the grace period allowing them entry to the Renewables Obligation beyond our propose closure date of 1 April 2016 will, by 18 June 2015, have to have planning consent, a grid connection offer and acceptance, and evidence of land rights for the site on which their project will be built. The precise grace period eligibility requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament. It will be for the developer of each individual project to determine whether they meet those eligibility requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","3217 ; 3218 ; 3219","2015-06-29T16:08:58.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383859/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383859/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power: Lincolnshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Written Statement of 18 June 2015, HC WS40, whether her Department plans to offer support under the Renewables Obligation to the proposed Sewstern Lane wind farm.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","3220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383860","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Government’s planning policy prevents the building of new coal power plants without carbon capture and storage and this is backed up by the Emissions Performance Standard which sets a limit on the carbon dioxide emissions from new fossil fuel plants.</p><p>Current policies are leading to the progressive decline in unabated coal generation. Coal accounted for 40% of total UK generation in 2012 falling to 29% in 2014. The Department’s analysis shows that unabated coal is expected to account for around 1% of total UK generation by 2025.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:55:30.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383860/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383860/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will publish a plan committing to phase-out coal without carbon capture technology from the power sector by 2032.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383861","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority are currently undertaking a review of competition in the energy market and are due to publish Provisional Findings and Possible Remedies (if required) shortly. The CMA has the necessary expertise to determine what problems exist in the energy market and identify appropriate solutions. This Government has committed to implement all relevant recommendations of the CMA.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:55:08.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383861/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383861/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will bring forward proposals for a regulated social tariff for all energy suppliers to ensure all low income customers automatically receive the cheapest tariff.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383862","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>Climate change is one of the most serious threats facing our world. It is not just a threat to the environment. It is also a threat to national and global security, poverty eradication and economic prosperity.</p><p>In their June statement G7 Leaders recognised that the science is clear, that we need to hold the increase in average global temperature to below 2 degrees C, and that the world therefore needs deep cuts in global greenhouse gas emissions, to transform energy sectors and to advance decarbonisation of the global economy over the course of this century.</p><p>The UK is doing its part. We were the first country to put in place a legally binding long-term target, and we have established five year carbon budgets for reducing emissions into the late 2020s. We met our first carbon budget last year, and according to our latest projections we are on track to meet the next two carbon budgets.<br> <br> All others also need to do their fair share too, which is why UK is working to influence other countries to take action, to secure a new global in Paris and by providing assistance to those developing countries who need it to reduce their emissions, especially the poorest and most vulnerable.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T15:19:37.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383862/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383862/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps the Government will be taking in the (a) short, (b) medium and (c) long-term to achieve the G7's goal of decarbonising the global economy by the end of this century.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","3247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383863","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>This information is not held by DECC. My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State’s Written Statement of 18 June 2015, HC WS40, proposed that onshore wind stations wishing to access the grace period allowing them to accredit under the Renewables Obligation up to the end of March 2017 will, as one of a number of specified conditions, have to have a grid connection offer and acceptance of that offer as of the date of the announcement. The precise eligibility and evidence requirements will be determined through the legislative process and are subject to approval by Parliament.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T15:59:25.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383863/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383863/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which onshore wind farms are registered as having a grid connection offer and acceptance.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","3144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383864","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>Onshore wind has made a valuable contribution to the UK energy mix in recent years but has now reached the point where there is enough capacity in the pipeline to help the UK meet its 2020 renewable commitments. The grace period arrangements that we have proposed are intended to protect investor confidence in the wider renewables sector and balance the interests of onshore wind developers with consumers, who pay the cost of onshore wind generation through their energy bill. DECC will continue to engage with developers, investors and stakeholders as we to implement the manifesto commitment. We will consider carefully the level of investment that developers are likely to bring forward under the proposals announced by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 18 June.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T15:58:28.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383864/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383864/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-18","Wind Power: Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she plans to take to develop the potential for on-shore wind in Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross constituency; and how she plans to take account of that potential in reviewing on-shore wind subsidies.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","3162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383865","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>Under the EU Water Framework Directive, ‘water bodies’ are the geographical units used to report the current quality of the water environment and set legally binding water body objectives. They are used in reporting progress to the European Commission on the implementation of the Directive.</p><p> </p><p>There are minimum size criteria for the size of water body that must be included in the plan. The updated river basin management plans that the Environment Agency will submit to the Secretary of State for her approval in the autumn will contain about 29,200 miles of river water bodies. This is approximately 1200 fewer miles of river water bodies, excluded because of their small size, than in the current river basin management plans.</p><p> </p><p>While the smaller river water bodies will not be reported in the plans, they are important and provide many benefits for people and wildlife. The laws protecting the quality of the water environment and the wildlife it supports apply to all rivers, regardless of whether they are in the river basin management plan.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-24T10:38:51.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383865/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383865/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-18","Rivers: Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what length of waterbodies is being removed from the current round of river basin management planning; and what assessment her Department has made of the effects on wildlife of removing those waterbodies.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","3164"
